snippet: Nebraska used to win in numbing, overwhelming fashion, but even the most spoiled fans are getting used to the current reality under Coach Bo Pelini.
lead_paragraph: I was walking through the office when a colleague stopped me. "Did I hear you say something about Nebraska football?" he asked, innocently, cheerfully, not realizing the twisted synapses that were about to fire in my brain. I frowned and shook my head over the idea of writing about the team. "My comments would be too blue," I assured him glibly.

snippet: ABC had its best end-of-the-year prime-time numbers since 2000 with coverage of the ball dropping in Times Square, according to preliminary results.
lead_paragraph: ABC extended "Dick Clark's New Year's Rockin' Eve" on Saturday night, and it appeared to pay off, giving the network its best end-of-the-year prime-time ratings since 2000. The two new hours of New Year's Eve merriment, from 8 to 10 p.m., drew about 8.3 million viewers, an unusually high number for a Saturday night. Repeats on the other networks drew between 1.5 million and 3 million viewers.
abstract: ABC had its best end-of-the-year prime-time numbers since 2000 with coverage of the ball dropping in Times Square, according to preliminary results.
headline: New Year's Rockin' Eve' Draws Strong Ratings

snippet: In no other sport does it seem necessary to embellish a perfectly good word like "ball."
lead_paragraph: It's a running joke in our office. One of our editors starts imitating a coach -- "To be a good football team, you have to protect the football, and then make some football plays" -- and others sometimes join in.
abstract: In no other sport does it seem necessary to embellish a perfectly good word like "ball."
headline: The Year in Football Language

snippet: One of Spain's most popular holiday events, the colorful Procession of the Three Kings, will proceed down the Paseo de la Castellana from Nuevos Ministerios to Plaza de Cibeles on Friday between 6:30 p.m. and 9 p.m.
lead_paragraph: One of Spain's most popular holiday events, the colorful Procession of the Three Kings, will proceed down the Paseo de la Castellana from Nuevos Ministerios to Plaza de Cibeles on Friday between 6:30 p.m. and 9 p.m. It features the elaborately dressed kings, their pages and helpers, who ride on floats distributing sweets to the children lining the route. There are at least 30 carriages, theatrical re-enactments, dancers, musicians, jugglers, street performers, royal pages, giant puppets and many other entertaining characters.According to the Bible, at this time of year, three wise and powerful kings brought gifts of gold, frankincense and myrrh to the infant Jesus. To celebrate the occasion, on Jan. 5, children in Spain go to bed early, awaiting the morning, when they hope to find the presents that they requested of the three kings in letters written on Boxing Day, Dec. 26. They leave shoes on windowsills or balconies or under the Christmas tree to be filled with toys.
abstract: One of Spain's most popular holiday events, the colorful Procession of the Three Kings, will proceed down the Paseo de la Castellana from Nuevos Ministerios to Plaza de Cibeles on Friday between 6:30 p.m. and 9 p.m.
headline: Madrid to Celebrate Three Kings, and the Gift of Innocence

snippet: Top magazine and long-form articles this week.
lead_paragraph: Joe Sacco, the well-known American cartoonist and journalist, uses his "comic journalism" lens on a rural district of Uttar Pradesh, India's largest and one of its poorest states. Caravan magazine publishes a long piece by him in its latest issue, which also includes a long profile of Imran Khan, the Pakistani cricketer turned politician. Mr. Sacco and an Indian journalist who assisted him, Piyush Srivastava, travel to the district Kushinagar near the border between Uttar Pradesh and Bihar to meet with poor and lower caste families.

snippet: <!-- ANDRES R. WAINER -->WAINER--Andres Rojas, 1942-2011. Former Agence France Presse and UPI Latin American Desk Correspondent; and later Chilean Press Attache to the US under President Salvador Allende died in his home on December 24, 2011 from...
lead_paragraph: WAINER--Andres Rojas, 1942-2011. Former Agence France Presse and UPI Latin American Desk Correspondent; and later Chilean Press Attache to the US under President Salvador Allende died in his home on December 24, 2011 from complications of primary systemic amyloidosis. In the latter half of his life Mr. Rojas was in private practice as a landscape designer. He lived in Petaluma, CA with his wife Catherine, daughter of renowned ophthalmologist Dr. Charles Schepens, and founder of Sausalito Springs, an early certified organic farm in California. He is survived by: his wife Catherine; his daughter Dr. Alicia Rojas, a physician and assistant professor at Columbia University Department of Psychiatry; and his son Clarence, artisan blacksmith and chief engineer for Pacific Coral Reed Foundation's new vessel's maiden voyage to Indonesia. There will be a private Memorial Service on January 7, 2012. Please call (415) 206-0230 for details. In lieu of flowers, please send donations: In memory of Andres Rojas Wainer, Amyloidosis Research at Mayo Clinic, 200 1st Street SW, Rochester, Minnesota 55905. Daniels Chapel of the Roses, Santa Rosa, CA (707) 525-3730
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  WAINER, ANDRES R.

snippet: <!-- MINTURN V. CHACE -->CHACE--Minturn V., 70, of Mt. Kisco, N.Y. died December 28, 2011 of cancer. "Mike" graduated from Milton Academy in 1959, Harvard College in 1963, and Harvard Business School in 1969 (MBA with distinction). He served in the...
lead_paragraph: CHACE--Minturn V., 70, of Mt. Kisco, N.Y. died December 28, 2011 of cancer. "Mike" graduated from Milton Academy in 1959, Harvard College in 1963, and Harvard Business School in 1969 (MBA with distinction). He served in the U.S. Navy from 1963 to 1967, as the ASW Officer on board the Destroyer Forrest Royal DD872. Mike was a management consultant and financial VP for several N.Y. firms. His favorite assignment was as Medical Coordinator for Project Orbis, the flying eye hospital. Most recently, he was a founding director of Bedford Management Group until retirement in 2006. Mike was active in the Episcopal Church of St. Matthews, Bedford. For 20 years he was President of Westmoreland Sanctuary for Wildlife and Forest Conservation. His passions were skiing, sailing and choral singing. Mike is mourned by his wife Helen Clay, daughters Martha and Susie, son-in-law John, former son-in-law Tom, four grandchildren, three sisters and one brother. Services will be held at St. Matthews, Rte. 22, Bedford on Monday, January 9th at 11AM. In lieu of flowers, donations may be sent to Westmoreland Sanctuary, 260 Chestnut Ridge Rd., Bedford Corners, N.Y. 10549; or to the Northeast Harbor Sailing School, P.O.Box 12, Northeast Harbor, ME 04662.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  CHACE, MINTURN V.

snippet: <!-- CONSTANTINE  SIDAMON-ERISTOFF -->SIDAMON-ERISTOFF-- Constantine. The Boards and staff of the National Audubon Society and Audubon New York are deeply saddened by the loss of our committed board member and a true leader, Constantine...
lead_paragraph: SIDAMON-ERISTOFF-- Constantine. The Boards and staff of the National Audubon Society and Audubon New York are deeply saddened by the loss of our committed board member and a true leader, Constantine Sidamon-Eristoff. As the founding Chair of Audubon New York, Connie was a consensus builder and knew how to help people and organizations find common ground. But, as a tenacious defender of the environment, he knew when to use the law and regulation to appropriate and maximum effect. He served on the Board of the National Audubon Society with passion and energy and was a model for his fellow members. Every day, he lived his life-long commitment to creating a healthy planet for wildlife and for generations of people to come. We are grateful for his dedication to conservation and public service. We extend our heartfelt sympathy to his wife Anne and the Sidamon-Eristoff family.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  SIDAMON-ERISTOFF, CONSTANTINE

snippet: <!-- ROSS  FLEISIG -->FLEISIG--Ross, an aerospace engineer for over 55 years, died in Binghamton, NY at age 90. Born in Montreal, Canada, Mr. Fleisig grew up in Forest Hills, Queens and lived most of his life in Garden City, New York. He received...
lead_paragraph: FLEISIG--Ross, an aerospace engineer for over 55 years, died in Binghamton, NY at age 90. Born in Montreal, Canada, Mr. Fleisig grew up in Forest Hills, Queens and lived most of his life in Garden City, New York. He received Bachelor's and Master's Degrees in Engineering from Polytechnic University. Mr. Fleisig enjoyed a long career as an aerospace engineer, working for Chance Vought Aircraft, Sperry Gyroscope Corporation, and the Grumman Corporation. As Spacecraft Team Manager at Grumman during the development of the Apollo Lunar Module, he directed a team integral to the success of the Apollo 11 LM-5 Eagle, the first spacecraft to land humans on the moon. Mr. Fleisig was a member of many professional organizations, including the American Astronautical Society, National Society of Professional Engineers, and American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics. He was an accomplished author and lecturer, receiving numerous honors from private and governmental organizations, and was also a member of the Mineola-Garden City Rotary Club, Garden City Casino, and the Garden City Ski Club. Mr. Fleisig was married to Marjorie Marie Hall, who predeceased him in 2000. He is survived by their two daughters Ann Machlin and Dale Gallis, and two grandchildren Russell Gallis and Thea Gallis Musselman.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  FLEISIG, ROSS

snippet: WERNER--Anne Power, died of cancer on Christmas Day 2011, at her home...
lead_paragraph: WERNER--Anne Power, died of cancer on Christmas Day 2011, at her home in North Hampton, New Hampshire. Anne has no immediate survivors. She does leave, however, her good friend, Father Daniel Morrissey, and a host of others enriched by their relationship with this extraordinary woman. Anne was born in Paris in 1928, the only child of Annabella, an international film star. In 1939 Annabella married the American actor, Tyrone Power, who adopted Anne. She always spoke fondly of Power, and he of her. On April 5, 1941, Tyrone wrote in his journal, "Today is Anni's birthday. I told Anni there was another present out front. She didn't say a word, just went over and touched the horse. After hugging the breath out of me, she kept whispering over and over again, â€˜My horse, my dear little horse." Anne grew up in the Hollywood of the 1940s, a dazzling time. Yet in her telling of it Anne was not dazzled. The simple joys of daily family life remained most vivid to her. Her parents entertained some of the most beautiful and celebrated people in the world, and from her upstairs room she could watch the arriving guests, the Clark Gables, the Gary Coopers, the Henry Fondas, Judy Garland. To Anne they were not celebrities, and certainly not icons, but rather friends of the family from down the street. From childhood Anne spoke French and English. In her twenties she became fluent in German. Throughout her life she read broadly in those languages, deepening her love of history. Her experience as a world traveler made her an informed conversationalist. She was thoughtful, articulate, an eager listener, who genuinely wanted to know what others had to say. Anne exercised horses at Longchamp Racecourse in Paris. She also taught actors to ride, and while on the set of Decision Before Dawn, she met Oskar Werner, a prominent actor in European classical theater and film. After they married in 1954, they travelled throughout the world as Oskar became an international film star, but they lived in Liechtenstein. Anne was always very grateful that she was able to come to know the great literature of the German language and the music and opera of Werner's native Austria. Their marriage ended in 1968. Anne returned to the United States, settling in North Hampton, a small New Hampshire seaside town. She put down roots which deepened over time, taking a position as an aide teaching deaf children to speak, a job she held for nearly twenty years. After retiring she continued to work as a volunteer at the North Hampton Library. In 1998 Anne designed and built a home filled with light and welcoming to guests. She lived only a mile from the ocean, which she loved in all its moods, and could walk to it almost every day. Anne kept close ties to France and returned each summer to Annabella's sheep farm, Contramundo, in the foothills of the Pyrenees, outside St Jean de Luz. There in the Basque countryside Anne welcomed many American friends together with Romanov emigres, writers, politicians and artists who visited her mother. For each guest Anne made the beauty and vitality of Contramundo a unique and unforgettable memory. Tolstoy writes in War and Peace, which Anne reread many times, "Love hinders death. Love is life. Everything, everything I understand, I understand only because I love. Everything is, everything exists, only because I love. Everything is connected only by that." Contributions in the name of Anne Power Werner may be made to the Public Broadcasting System, 2100 Crystal Drive, Arlington, VA 22201, or to the New Hampshire Public Radio, 2 Pillsbury Street, Suite 600, Concord, NH 03301. To sign an on line guest book, please visit www.brewittfuneralhome.com
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  WERNER, ANNE

snippet: <!-- DONALD J SIEWERT -->SIEWERT--Donald J., 72, formerly of New York City, died peacefully at his home in Baltimore, MD, on December 20, 2011. Beloved husband of Meg Savage Siewert. Devoted father of Kathleen (Arnob) Banerjee and Stephen (Karen)...
lead_paragraph: SIEWERT--Donald J., 72, formerly of New York City, died peacefully at his home in Baltimore, MD, on December 20, 2011. Beloved husband of Meg Savage Siewert. Devoted father of Kathleen (Arnob) Banerjee and Stephen (Karen) Siewert. Loving grandfather of Anju and Kaya Banerjee and Shannon Siewert. Dear brother of Lawrence (Nancy) Siewert, Susan Gramling, Teresa (Fran) Pierce, and Mary Pat Siewert. Esteemed brother-in-law of Andrew J., (Cheryl) Savage. Also survived by other loving family members and friends. Don received a M.A. in Philosophy from St. Louis University and taught at Marquette University, the Catholic University of America, and the University of Missouri. Don earned a J.D. from Columbia Law School. He served as an Assistant District Attorney in the Office of the New York County District Attorney for 31 years and retired as Deputy Chief of the Appeals Bureau. A gathering will be held on January 6, 2012, 7-9pm. Mass of the Resurrection, Saturday, January 7, 2012, 10:00am, St. Mary of the Assumption Church, 5502 York Rd., Baltimore, MD, 21212. Memorial contributions may be made to Gilchrist Hospice Care, 11311 McCormick Rd., Suite 350, Hunt Valley, MD, 21031, or the University of Maryland Fund for Medicine, 100 North Greene St., Suite 600, Baltimore, MD, 21201. Inquiries may be directed to the family-owned Mitchell-Wiedefeld Funeral Home, Inc., (410) 377-8300.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  SIEWERT, DONALD J.

snippet: <!-- ALVIN M POPLACK -->POPLACK--Rabbi Alvin Myron, 91, died on December 24, 2011 with his three children by his side. He was predeceased by 66 days by his wife of 66 years, the former Rosalind Schachter. Son of Rabbi Alter and Genia Trakeniski...
lead_paragraph: POPLACK--Rabbi Alvin Myron, 91, died on December 24, 2011 with his three children by his side. He was predeceased by 66 days by his wife of 66 years, the former Rosalind Schachter. Son of Rabbi Alter and Genia Trakeniski Poplack, he was ordained at Rabbinical Seminary Chaim Berlin (New York) in 1944. Rabbi Poplack held a Masters from Yeshiva University, and a PhD from Jewish Teachers Seminary. During WWII he served as civilian chaplain in the USO Jewish Welfare Board. He held pulpits in Detroit, MI, Medford, MA, and Lebanon, PA before becoming Rabbi (1956) and Rabbi Emeritus (1986) of the Bellerose Jewish Center (New York). He served as President of the Queens Council for Soviet Jewry, and Secretary of the New York Board of Rabbis. As Senior Chaplain, Rabbi Poplack spearheaded the reconstruction of the International Synagogue at JFK Airport, and was spiritual leader to the JFK community and travelers from all over the world. He was the author of Carved In Granite: Holocaust Memorials in Metropolitan New York Jewish Cemeteries (2003), a work read and endorsed by leading Holocaust scholars. He is profoundly missed by his loving children, grandchildren, great-grandchildren, and by family, friends, colleagues, former congregants and the countless people whose lives he touched.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  POPLACK, ALVIN M.

snippet: MILLER--Dorothee C. 1933-2011. Quogue, New York resident Dorothee...
lead_paragraph: MILLER--Dorothee C. 1933-2011. Quogue, New York resident Dorothee C. Miller died on Tuesday, December 20 of cirrhosis of the liver at Stony Brook Medical Center after a five-week hospitalization. She was 78. Ms. Miller was the daughter of Sophie and Lester Cornelius. She grew up in Richmond Hill, NY and attended Jamaica High School, thereafter working variously at The Sperry Company and The Singer Company. She also worked part-time as a fashion and television model for The Harry Conover Agency and Pendleton. Later in life, she went back to school, receiving two Associate Degrees from Queens College, New York. She was predeceased in 1998 by her beloved husband of 21 years, Willie, as well as her cherished longtime companion Robert Lovett, Sr. of Hampton Bays, NY in 2008. Dorothee was always cheery and quick with a smile, generous in her hospitality, unwavering in her opinions, independent to the last, and she will be missed greatly by her family and many friends. Ms. Miller is survived by her sister and brother-in-law, Joan and Richard Gibbs of Oak Creek, CO, her son and daughter-in-law, Todd and Lenore Evans of Remsenburg, NY, her son and daughter-in-law, Scott and Cynthia Evans of Chestertown, NY, and her grandchildren Alyssa, Cole, Casey, Kristin, Cody, and Jessie. According to Ms. Miller's wishes, there will be no funeral or memorial services. Her cremains will be scattered across Long Island Sound by her family. The family would appreciate that in lieu of flowers, a gift donation be made to The Betty Ford Legacy Fund in memory of Dorothee Miller, either online, or by calling 800-854-9211 x4105.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  MILLER, DOROTHEE C.

lead_paragraph: England's Football Association on Saturday released the 115-page report compiled by an independent commission that suspended Liverpool striker Luis Suárez for eight games. snippet: FRANKENTHALER--Helen The family of Helen Frankenthaler, the eminent American abstract painter, announced with profound sadness her death at the age of 83, on December 27, 2011, at her home in Connecticut after a long illness. Deeply loved by her...
lead_paragraph: FRANKENTHALER--Helen The family of Helen Frankenthaler, the eminent American abstract painter, announced with profound sadness her death at the age of 83, on December 27, 2011, at her home in Connecticut after a long illness. Deeply loved by her family and cherished by her many friends around the world, she is survived by her husband of seventeen years, Stephen M. DuBrul, Jr.; and by her nieces, Ellen Iseman and Beverly Ross, and four nephews, Peter Iseman, Fred Iseman, Alfred Ross, and Clifford Ross. She is also survived by two stepdaughters, Lise Motherwell and Jeannie Motherwell, from her first marriage, to the artist Robert Motherwell, and by two stepchildren, Jennifer DuBrul and Nicholas DuBrul, as well as three grandnephews, two grandnieces, four step-granddaughters, two step-great-grandsons, and one step-great-granddaughter. Helen Frankenthaler was born in Manhattan in 1928, the third daughter of New York State Supreme Court Judge Alfred Frankenthaler and Martha Lowenstein Frankenthaler. Her sisters, Marjorie Frankenthaler Iseman and Gloria Frankenthaler Ross Bookman, predeceased her. Helen Frankenthaler graduated from The Dalton School, having attended The Brearley School and The Horace Mann School. A 1949 graduate of Bennington College, she served as a member of the College's Board of Trustees from 1967 to 1982. She was the recipient of twenty-six honorary degrees, as well as other notable honors, including the National Medal of the Arts, in 2001. Most recently, she was appointed as an Honorary Academician of the Royal Academy of Arts, London in 2011. From 1985 to 1992, she was a member of the National Council on the Arts, part of the National Endowment for the Arts. A perfectionist and planner to the end, she made clear her wish to be buried at her alma mater, Bennington College, in Vermont, where a private ceremony will be held. A memorial service in New York City will be announced in the weeks ahead. In lieu of flowers, donations may be made in her memory to Bennington College or Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, New York City. Helen was a family treasure, a national treasure, and will be forever missed by those who knew her well and by a public who admired her vibrant works of art. In her career she was an original, brilliant, energetic, witty presence who shone brightly in our firmament. With her passing, her world and her family are left with a deep void and diminished color.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  FRANKENTHALER, HELEN

snippet: In 1958, Richard and Mildred Loving were arrested in a nighttime raid in their bedroom by the sheriff of Caroline County, Va. Their crime: being married to each other. The Lovings -- Mildred, who was of African-American and Native American descent,...
lead_paragraph: In 1958, Richard and Mildred Loving were arrested in a nighttime raid in their bedroom by the sheriff of Caroline County, Va. Their crime: being married to each other. The Lovings -- Mildred, who was of African-American and Native American descent, and Richard, a bricklayer with a blond buzz cut -- were ordered by a judge to leave Virginia for 25 years. This month, the International Center of Photography is mounting a show of Grey Villet's photographs of the couple. That exhibit is complemented by an HBO documentary telling the story of the Lovings' struggle to return home after living in exile in Washington, where Mildred, gentle in person but persistent on paper, wrote pleading letters to Robert F. Kennedy and the A.C.L.U. Two lawyers took their case to the Supreme Court, whichstruck down miscegenation laws in more than a dozen states. The Lovings' belief in the simple rightness of their plea never wavered. Asked by one of his lawyers if he had a message for the Supreme Court, Richard said he did: ''Tell the court I love my wife.'' Number of states where interracial marriage was illegal in 1958: 24
headline: The Case of Loving v. Bigotry

snippet: From farmers to power plant operators to homeowners, everyone in Texas is wondering when the grueling 15-month drought will end. The answer, alas, is that nobody knows.      Recent rain and snow have pushed state precipitation totals above the...
lead_paragraph: From farmers to power plant operators to homeowners, everyone in Texas is wondering when the grueling 15-month drought will end. The answer, alas, is that nobody knows. Recent rain and snow have pushed state precipitation totals above the average for December, but this appears to be ''a short-term aberration in an overall long-term dry pattern,'' Victor Murphy, a southern regional official with the National Weather Service, said in an e-mail.
headline: Praying For Rain; Lots of It

snippet: If you were to go back to ancient Rome in the gladiatorial arena, you would find a similar power structure to what we have in today's sports: owners, players and fans (though in those days, owners received a lot more than 51 percent of total...
lead_paragraph: If you were to go back to ancient Rome in the gladiatorial arena, you would find a similar power structure to what we have in today's sports: owners, players and fans (though in those days, owners received a lot more than 51 percent of total revenue). That familiar structure was turned on its head this year when the Dallas Mavericks defeated the Miami Heat in the N.B.A. finals and the Larry O'Brien Trophy was presented to an owner who seemed much more like a fan.
abstract: Benjamin Hoffman offers a notable sports moment from 2011; remembers Dallas Mavericks NBA championship victory over Miami Heat and Mavericks owner Mark Cuban's unbridled joy when presented with the trophy. Photo (M)
headline: 2011: An Owner Who Is a Fan At Heart

snippet: An opinion essay on Dec. 11 about anti-Catholic prejudice during the 1928 presidential campaign of Alfred E. Smith referred imprecisely to Hugh L. Carey, and a correction in this space on Dec. 18 erroneously attributed a distinction to Mr. Smith....
lead_paragraph: An opinion essay on Dec. 11 about anti-Catholic prejudice during the 1928 presidential campaign of Alfred E. Smith referred imprecisely to Hugh L. Carey, and a correction in this space on Dec. 18 erroneously attributed a distinction to Mr. Smith. While Mr. Smith (who served from 1919 to 1920 and again from 1923 to 1928) was the first Catholic to be elected governor of New York State (and Mr. Carey, who served from 1975 to 1982, was the second), Mr. Smith was not the first Catholic governor. The correction also referred incorrectly to Malcolm Wilson, governor from 1973 to 1974. He was one of several Catholics who succeeded to the position without having been elected (including Martin H. Glynn, who served from 1913 to 1914 and was the state's first Catholic governor). Neither Mr. Wilson nor Mr. Carey was the second Catholic governor; Mr. Smith was.
headline: CORRECTION

snippet: The drumbeat of anticipation for the game between No. 1 Louisiana State and No. 2 Alabama began in September and reached a fever pitch by early November. It was billed as a once-a-decade regular-season game until it suddenly did not matter anymore.  ...
lead_paragraph: The drumbeat of anticipation for the game between No. 1 Louisiana State and No. 2 Alabama began in September and reached a fever pitch by early November. It was billed as a once-a-decade regular-season game until it suddenly did not matter anymore. On the morning of Nov. 5, a grand jury report became public and once again put the focus of the college sports world far off the field. The report described child sexual abuse accusations against the former Penn State assistant football coach Jerry Sandusky, which set off a firestorm that cost the jobs of Joe Paterno, the longtime coach, and Graham B. Spanier, the university president.
abstract: Pete Thamel notes that in college sports, 2011 will be remembered as the year when the action on the field was often inconsequential compared with the scandals that blazed off it; says nothing crystallized that feeling for him better than the LSU-Alabama kickoff, when news of Jerry Sandusky's arrest for sexual abuse overshadowed the much anticipated Nov 5 game. Photo (M)
headline: 2011: Distracting, Distressing Year in College Sports

snippet: Readers respond.
lead_paragraph: According to the quote from the unelected Mr. Harris about the city finance director he fired: ''He was smart and articulate, but he just wasn't doing anything that I couldn't do.'' Is that the new criterion for dissolving democracy? I find this situation very troubling. If a corporation has laudable reasons for establishing a company town, it should do the things that uplift the residents and help them participate in their own stability. It is obvious that what Whirlpool and the current state government were really after was a takeover of the shorefront property for a resort that benefits the wealthy outsiders and edges out the undesirable community who has been gifted the shorefront land. Being poor does not negate protection under the law and does not eliminate any American's constitutional rights. NORMA, Albuquerque, posted on nytimes.com
headline: The Strange Second Life of a Michigan Factory Town

snippet: WERNER--Anne Power, died of cancer on Christmas Day 2011, at her home in North Hampton, New Hampshire. Anne has no immediate survivors. She does leave, however, her good friend, Father Daniel Morrissey, and a host of others enriched by their...
lead_paragraph: WERNER--Anne Power, died of cancer on Christmas Day 2011, at her home in North Hampton, New Hampshire. Anne has no immediate survivors. She does leave, however, her good friend, Father Daniel Morrissey, and a host of others enriched by their relationship with this extraordinary woman. Anne was born in Paris in 1928, the only child of Annabella, an international film star. In 1939 Annabella married the American actor, Tyrone Power, who adopted Anne. She always spoke fondly of Power, and he of her. On April 5, 1941, Tyrone wrote in his journal, "Today is Anni's birthday. I told Anni there was another present out front. She didn't say a word, just went over and touched the horse. After hugging the breath out of me, she kept whispering over and over again, My horse, my dear little horse." Anne grew up in the Hollywood of the 1940s, a dazzling time. Yet in her telling of it Anne was not dazzled. The simple joys of daily family life remained most vivid to her. Her parents entertained some of the most beautiful and celebrated people in the world, and from her upstairs room she could watch the arriving guests, the Clark Gables, the Gary Coopers, the Henry Fondas, Judy Garland. To Anne they were not celebrities, and certainly not icons, but rather friends of the family from down the street. From childhood Anne spoke French and English. In her twenties she became fluent in German. Throughout her life she read broadly in those languages, deepening her love of history. Her experience as a world traveler made her an informed conversationalist. She was thoughtful, articulate, an eager listener, who genuinely wanted to know what others had to say. Anne exercised horses at Longchamp Racecourse in Paris. She also taught actors to ride, and while on the set of Decision Before Dawn, she met Oskar Werner, a prominent actor in European classical theater and film. After they married in 1954, they travelled throughout the world as Oskar became an international film star, but they lived in Liechtenstein. Anne was always very grateful that she was able to come to know the great literature of the German language and the music and opera of Werner's native Austria. Their marriage ended in 1968. Anne returned to the United States, settling in North Hampton, a small New Hampshire seaside town. She put down roots which deepened over time, taking a position as an aide teaching deaf children to speak, a job she held for nearly twenty years. After retiring she continued to work as a volunteer at the North Hampton Library. In 1998 Anne designed and built a home filled with light and welcoming to guests. She lived only a mile from the ocean, which she loved in all its moods, and could walk to it almost every day. Anne kept close ties to France and returned each summer to Annabella's sheep farm, Contramundo, in the foothills of the Pyrenees, outside St Jean de Luz. There in the Basque countryside Anne welcomed many American friends together with Romanov emigres, writers, politicians and artists who visited her mother. For each guest Anne made the beauty and vitality of Contramundo a unique and unforgettable memory. Tolstoy writes in War and Peace, which Anne reread many times, "Love hinders death. Love is life. Everything, everything I understand, I understand only because I love. Everything is, everything exists, only because I love. Everything is connected only by that." Contributions in the name of Anne Power Werner may be made to the Public Broadcasting System, 2100 Crystal Drive, Arlington, VA 22201, or to the New Hampshire Public Radio, 2 Pillsbury Street, Suite 600, Concord, NH 03301. To sign an on line guest book, please visit www.brewittfuneralhome.com
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  WERNER, ANNE POWER

snippet: This year, for the first time in decades, New Yorkers will be allowed to hail livery cabs legally on the street. Thousands of cars, not painted yellow but equipped with meters and credit-card readers, will be licensed to pick up fares outside of busy...
lead_paragraph: This year, for the first time in decades, New Yorkers will be allowed to hail livery cabs legally on the street. Thousands of cars, not painted yellow but equipped with meters and credit-card readers, will be licensed to pick up fares outside of busy parts of Manhattan. How the zones will be enforced remains an open question. If you can't still find a taxi, you may be able to rent a bike. By summertime, the city will unveil an ambitious bike-sharing system, with 10,000 bicycles available for short-term rentals at 600 locations in Manhattan and Brooklyn. Similar programs are immensely popular in London, Paris and Washington, but critics worry about congestion, safety and where the kiosks will be placed.
abstract: Michael M Grynbaum predicts developments in livery cab laws, bike-sharing and tolls, among other transportation issues, in New York City for 2012. Drawing (M)
headline: Transportation

snippet: CAROLINA HERRERA BÁEZ, not to be confused with her mother, Carolina Herrera, has been a quiet influence in her family's atelier for most of her life. But it isn't until now, with the introduction of her own accessory, that she could call herself a...
lead_paragraph: CAROLINA HERRERA BÁEZ, not to be confused with her mother, Carolina Herrera, has been a quiet influence in her family's atelier for most of her life. But it isn't until now, with the introduction of her own accessory, that she could call herself a designer. The Mini Matryoshka bag, a bucket tote in Goya leather, comes in seven Bauhaus-inspired color blocks, like canary yellow and grass green, or a Mondrian-esque red and black. There is much in the capsule that can be credited to her mother. ''She has a small-purse philosophy,'' Ms. Herrera Báez said, explaining why, for example, the bag is the compact size that it is. ''You carry only what is essential.'' But the graphic look and feel are original. ''Sometimes, great ideas on paper are just that,'' Ms. Herrera Báez said. ''The ability to fine-tune an aesthetic in tandem with intuition is a good trait for any designer to have.'' Tuck that one in your tote. Carolina Herrera Mini Matryoshka bag, $470 at CH Carolina Herrera boutiques; (212) 744-2076. CHELSEA ZALOPANY
abstract: Carolina Herrera Baez introduces the Mini Matryoshka, a small brightly colored bucket tote bag inspired by her mother, the fashion designer Carolina Herrera. Photo (S)¿
headline: A Mother-and-Daughter Bag

snippet: The consequences of lawmakers' roughly $5.4 billion reduction in state financing to public education in 2011 will dominate 2012. The budget slashing has already galvanized more than half of the school districts in Texas into four different lawsuits...
lead_paragraph: The consequences of lawmakers' roughly $5.4 billion reduction in state financing to public education in 2011 will dominate 2012. The budget slashing has already galvanized more than half of the school districts in Texas into four different lawsuits against the state, which will wind up in court next fall. In March, official numbers of how many and what types of employees were laid off by school districts will be released, just before the primaries -- the first real indicator of the budget cuts' political ramifications. Also in the spring, the state's approximately 350,000 ninth graders will be the first to take the end-of-course exams that are part of Texas' new standardized testing system.
headline: Lawsuits, New Tests, More Cuts

snippet: BUCK--Richard M.,"Dick," 81, on December 20, 2011. Only child of Earl R. and Florence M. Buck from Kendall, NY. BA and MA, SUNY Albany; MS, Columbia University. Dick joined the New York Public Library system in 1959 and in 1967 began his 30-year...
lead_paragraph: BUCK--Richard M.,"Dick," 81, on December 20, 2011. Only child of Earl R. and Florence M. Buck from Kendall, NY. BA and MA, SUNY Albany; MS, Columbia University. Dick joined the New York Public Library system in 1959 and in 1967 began his 30-year tenure as Administrator at the Library for the Performing Arts, where he initiated and directed a multitude of exhibits, galas and fundraisers, including the annual "White Elephant Bazaars." He was Secretary-Treasurer of the Theater Library Association from 1970-96 and Councilor of the American Library Association from 1990-94. In 1997, Dick moved permanently to Miami Beach, where he was active until his final years with the Miami Design Preservation League. He is survived by a cousin, Dennis Buck of Manhattan. Memorial to be held on January 6th from 6-8pm at the Mantell Plaza, 255 W. 24th St., Miami Beach, FL 33140.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  BUCK, RICHARD M.

snippet: SIEWERT--Donald J.,72, formerly of New York City, died peacefully at his home in Baltimore, MD, on December 20, 2011. Beloved husband of Meg Savage Siewert. Devoted father of Kathleen (Arnob) Banerjee and Stephen (Karen) Siewert. Loving grandfather...
lead_paragraph: SIEWERT--Donald J.,72, formerly of New York City, died peacefully at his home in Baltimore, MD, on December 20, 2011. Beloved husband of Meg Savage Siewert. Devoted father of Kathleen (Arnob) Banerjee and Stephen (Karen) Siewert. Loving grandfather of Anju and Kaya Banerjee and Shannon Siewert. Dear brother of Lawrence (Nancy) Siewert, Susan Gramling, Teresa (Fran) Pierce, and Mary Pat Siewert. Esteemed brother-in-law of Andrew J., (Cheryl) Savage. Also survived by other loving family members and friends. Don received a M.A. in Philosophy from St. Louis University and taught at Marquette University, the Catholic University of America, and the University of Missouri. Don earned a J.D. from Columbia Law School. He served as an Assistant District Attorney in the Office of the New York County District Attorney for 31 years and retired as Deputy Chief of the Appeals Bureau. A gathering will be held on January 6, 2012, 7-9pm. Mass of the Resurrection, Saturday, January 7, 2012, 10:00am, St. Mary of the Assumption Church, 5502 York Rd., Baltimore, MD, 21212. Memorial contributions may be made to Gilchrist Hospice Care, 11311 McCormick Rd., Suite 350, Hunt Valley, MD, 21031, or the University of Maryland Fund for Medicine, 100 North Greene St., Suite 600, Baltimore, MD, 21201. Inquiries may be directed to the family-owned Mitchell-Wiedefeld Funeral Home, Inc., (410) 377-8300.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  SIEWERT, DONALD J.

snippet: Ronan, 14: Last spring I decided: no more being a guy; I want to be a girl. I've felt it coming for maybe two years. Then last spring I tried it, and I thought I'd just go for it. I dress like a girl too. I like it so far. I go to a school called...
lead_paragraph: Ronan, 14: Last spring I decided: no more being a guy; I want to be a girl. I've felt it coming for maybe two years. Then last spring I tried it, and I thought I'd just go for it. I dress like a girl too. I like it so far. I go to a school called FACE, and it's very open, so no one was surprised. I'm not the only person who does this. I wake up at about 5:40 every morning. Usually I'll stay in bed five minutes, then I'll take a shower, blow-dry my hair and brush it out. Then I'll get dressed and do my makeup. I do my own makeup. My mom doesn't do makeup with me. She doesn't like makeup. The earrings I got as a gift. I think my grandmother gave them to me.
abstract: What They Were Thinking interview with Ronan, a 14-year-old transvestite student from Montreal, Canada, who comments on a photograph taken of him putting on makeup in the bathroom at his school. Photo (S)
headline: In The Boys' Room, Montreal

snippet: A Corps of Engineers study of cargo shipping on Chicago-area waterways has added to the debate on their role in the economy’s future.
lead_paragraph: A new Army Corps of Engineersstudy of Chicago-area waterways has stirred the debate over whether to sever the connection between Lake Michigan and inland waterways that were created by the construction of canals a century ago. The study, released on Dec. 7, is part of the Corps's nearly decade-long process aimed at preventing invasive species, including voracious Asian carp, from spreading between the Great Lakes and the Mississippi River ecosystems. But how to achieve that environmental goal has become bound up with varying predictions of what the future of shipping in the Midwest, and even farther South, will be.
headline: Study of Waterways Stirs Debate on Roles In the Region's Future

snippet: AT the start of a promising new year -- and let's face it, they're all promising -- how much of the city really cares about you? You think steel cares? Steel is cold. Glass? Glass will cut you.      Neon cares. Neon wants you to come inside where...
lead_paragraph: AT the start of a promising new year -- and let's face it, they're all promising -- how much of the city really cares about you? You think steel cares? Steel is cold. Glass? Glass will cut you. Neon cares. Neon wants you to come inside where it's warm. It promises everything that lures people to New York: temptation and salvation, sustenance and health, romance and prophecy. No two neon signs are alike, and individual signs change over time, starting to flicker or losing a letter. Even at its most knowing, neon keeps its innocence.
abstract: Photographer Kirsten Hively has created online gallery of photos documenting neon signs in New York City, which are steadily being replaced by LED and video displays. Photos (M)
headline: The Lights That Beckon The City

snippet: Hotel restaurants often reinvent themselves to keep up with food trends. At a time when new is the norm, though, some long-standing restaurants are sticking to tried and true.      The Polo Lounge at the Beverly Hills Hotel, which is celebrating its...
lead_paragraph: Hotel restaurants often reinvent themselves to keep up with food trends. At a time when new is the norm, though, some long-standing restaurants are sticking to tried and true. The Polo Lounge at the Beverly Hills Hotel, which is celebrating its 100th anniversary this year, is one of those exceptions. It opened in 1949 with an American menu, and six of its original dishes are still available. Two of them -- the tortilla soup and the McCarthy salad, above -- make up 15 percent of the sales for the restaurant.
abstract: In Transit blog; some hotel restaurants are bucking the trend of reinventing themselves, sticking to tried and true menus. Photo (M)

snippet: It was not a stellar year for huge sport utility vehicles, and the big news in pickup trucks was hidden under the hood -- Ford's shift to an efficient V-6 engine, replacing a thirsty base-level V-8 in its perennially bestselling F-150.     A wave of...
lead_paragraph: It was not a stellar year for huge sport utility vehicles, and the big news in pickup trucks was hidden under the hood -- Ford's shift to an efficient V-6 engine, replacing a thirsty base-level V-8 in its perennially bestselling F-150. A wave of new electric cars and plug-in hybrids may be on the way, but the internal combustion engine showed no signs of stepping aside for an upstart successor. On the contrary, some new models were powered by gasoline-burning piston engines, often in downsized form and paired with ultra efficient transmissions, that delivered mileage nearly unthinkable a few years ago.
abstract: Introduction to Automobiles Critics' Picks section, where reviewers select most memorable cars of 2011. (S)
headline: Critics' Picks of 2011: Making Sense of a More Sensible Year

snippet: IT was pitch black at 8:30 a.m. on a frigid Icelandic morning, but at least there was no snow falling. Though cloud cover the night before had scuttled my chance to see the Northern Lights, my plan for a 36-hour road trip from Reykjavik, ending a...
lead_paragraph: IT was pitch black at 8:30 a.m. on a frigid Icelandic morning, but at least there was no snow falling. Though cloud cover the night before had scuttled my chance to see the Northern Lights, my plan for a 36-hour road trip from Reykjavik, ending a great four days in Iceland, was in full effect. I had spent the previous day's precious daylight hours (about five at this time of year) seeing the geysers, waterfalls and icy landscapes of the Golden Circle, a popular route that loops northeast from the capital of Reykjavik and back again. When the sun disappeared, at about 3 p.m., I headed southeast to the snow-covered coast, skirting imposing mountains to arrive at a guesthouse called Vellir, on Route 219 off the main highway, where I planned to spend the night. I was to get moving before the sun rose, driving the 10 miles to Vik -- supposedly a picturesque village of 300 people, black sand beaches and amazing rock formations.
abstract: Seth Kugel Frugal Traveler column on traveling to Reykjavik, Iceland. Photos (M)1
headline: Warming Up Short Days, Long Nights in Iceland

snippet: Here's a sampling of readers' responses to Alastair Macaulay's column on the choreographer Merce Cunningham as his company completed its two-year legacy tour.     ''Without the bias of an education in dance, I came to Merce on my own. Sitting in the...
lead_paragraph: Here's a sampling of readers' responses to Alastair Macaulay's column on the choreographer Merce Cunningham as his company completed its two-year legacy tour. ''Without the bias of an education in dance, I came to Merce on my own. Sitting in the rafters at City Center every March, I'd watch the legions leave halfway through, unable to grasp the language of his gestures or the sounds that accompanied them. Years later when coincidence led me to share my life for some years with a dancer in the company, Merce admitted his pleasure at testing the limits of his audience, suggesting in not so many words that the ones who made it through somehow earned the pleasures he suffered, and earned, in his own art.''
headline: COMMENTS

snippet: In the wake of its latest high-profile exoneration, the Texas criminal justice community is grappling with the issue of prosecutorial misconduct.     Murder charges against Michael Morton have been officially dismissed, and he is now out of prison...
lead_paragraph: In the wake of its latest high-profile exoneration, the Texas criminal justice community is grappling with the issue of prosecutorial misconduct. Murder charges against Michael Morton have been officially dismissed, and he is now out of prison after 25 years, but the ramifications of his case have just begun. His lawyers have asked a Texas court to launch an unprecedented inquiry into whether Ken Anderson, the prosecutor who secured Mr. Morton's conviction, ought to face criminal charges and professional discipline.
headline: Prosecutorial Misconduct Moves to Front of Agenda

snippet: When the Big City Book Club reconvenes for its next online literary discussion on Jan. 10, we will be talking about Alfred Kazin's ''A Walker in the City,'' the writer's 1951 memoir of growing up in Brownsville, Brooklyn.      The book is a...
lead_paragraph: When the Big City Book Club reconvenes for its next online literary discussion on Jan. 10, we will be talking about Alfred Kazin's ''A Walker in the City,'' the writer's 1951 memoir of growing up in Brownsville, Brooklyn. The book is a celebration of Mr. Kazin's poor immigrant childhood in the pushcart universe of 1920s and '30s Jewish New York. It is also a record of his path out of that world, and his arrival among the New York Intellectuals, the storied group of Jewish writers and social theorists who graduated from City College and included Daniel Bell, Nathan Glazer and Irving Howe, among others.
headline: Big City Book Club

snippet: When I was young, I played a dice baseball game for hundreds of hours a year. My favorite part of managing was using the bullpen. I loved all the random names bunched together on the stat sheet with the big stars.     Sometimes, I recreated old World...
lead_paragraph: When I was young, I played a dice baseball game for hundreds of hours a year. My favorite part of managing was using the bullpen. I loved all the random names bunched together on the stat sheet with the big stars. Sometimes, I recreated old World Series by studying the cumulative box scores in the Baseball Encyclopedia. I tried to use everybody. How awful it would feel, I reasoned, to be eligible for the World Series but never play.

snippet: COVERING more than two decades, ''Pretty Much Everything'' (Taschen, $700) is the first comprehensive monograph of the work of the Dutch wife-and-husband photo team Inez van Lamsweerde and Vinoodh Matadin. The three-volume set, which includes a...
lead_paragraph: COVERING more than two decades, ''Pretty Much Everything'' (Taschen, $700) is the first comprehensive monograph of the work of the Dutch wife-and-husband photo team Inez van Lamsweerde and Vinoodh Matadin. The three-volume set, which includes a silkscreen print, jumbles together 666 photos. Some were originally ads; others first appeared in gallery shows. The resulting mix, in which glamorous celebrity portraits meet androgynous fine-art photos and manneristic fashion editorials, may seem a bit schizophrenic. But Ms. van Lamsweerde said that the book was constructed to show that these distinct genres matter less and less, at least for globally in-demand photographers like them. ''Sometimes our work that's been published as an advertising campaign ends up on the walls of a museum,'' she said. Above, ''Hilary and Irina at the St. Regis Hotel,'' originally published in 2006 in Self Service magazine. STEPHEN HEYMAN
abstract: Dutch wife-and-husband photo team Inez van Lamsweerde and Vinoodh Matadin publish three-volume monograph entitled Pretty Much Everything, which features 666 photographs they created for both ads and gallery shows. Photo (S)
headline: Borderless Photos

snippet: Gambling is becoming a blood sport among developers. Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo wants a constitutional amendment to legalize full casino gambling. That's the easy part. There are already nine racetrack casinos and six American Indian casinos in New York....
lead_paragraph: Gambling is becoming a blood sport among developers. Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo wants a constitutional amendment to legalize full casino gambling. That's the easy part. There are already nine racetrack casinos and six American Indian casinos in New York. But the battle will be fierce over how many new casinos to allow, and where. The racetracks don't want competition. Other interests would cut the ties between casino gambling and horse racing. The Seneca and Oneida Nations oppose legalization. The Las Vegas and Atlantic City outfits favor casinos everywhere, especially in Manhattan; otherwise they will try to kill the amendment. What will Donald J. Trump or Stephen A. Wynn do? In the meantime, it's a full employment act for the lobbyists.
abstract: Charles V Bagli predicts developments in commercial and residential real estate in New York City in 2012 and speculates on how fierce the battle over legalized gambling will become among New York State developers intent on getting a piece of the action in building new casinos. snippet: As her band the Little Willies prepares to release its second album, Norah Jones talks about the music that influenced her.
lead_paragraph: It took Norah Jones precisely one year to become a household name. Her debut album, ''Come Away With Me,'' was released in February 2002, and by the following February it had sold four million copies and she had won five Grammys. A side project she created the following year is less well known. As a diversion from the pressures of following up one of the best-selling debuts of all time, Ms. Jones and four friends formed the band the Little Willies (named after her childhood hero, Willie Nelson) and began playing her favorite country songs at a series of unannounced gigs at the Living Room, a tiny music venue in New York.
headline: Norah Jones and the Music She Loves

snippet: All signs point to the public release of performance rankings for thousands of New York City teachers in 2012. The records rate 12,000 of the city's 75,000 teachers and are based on how much progress students made on the state's standardized tests, a...
lead_paragraph: All signs point to the public release of performance rankings for thousands of New York City teachers in 2012. The records rate 12,000 of the city's 75,000 teachers and are based on how much progress students made on the state's standardized tests, a controversial measurement tool. After several court rulings favoring the rankings' disclosure, the teachers' union is running out of legal options to keep them confidential. Losing on this issue would not be likely to undermine the union's political clout, though. Public education will undoubtedly play a central role in the 2013 mayoral race, and candidates will be expected to lay out their visions for the future once their campaigns pick up steam. One key question will be whether they will push to keep the schools under mayoral control.
abstract: Fernanda Santos predicts developments for New York City teachers in 2012. Drawing (M)
headline: Education

snippet: 1 ''Give me time, and I'll give you a revolution,'' Alexander McQueen once said. Like anyone born to achieve, he resented the small distractions -- and the fashion business provides plenty of them. Well, even he probably never dreamed that 661,509...
lead_paragraph: 1 ''Give me time, and I'll give you a revolution,'' Alexander McQueen once said. Like anyone born to achieve, he resented the small distractions -- and the fashion business provides plenty of them. Well, even he probably never dreamed that 661,509 people would go to the Metropolitan Museum of Art to see his clothes. What were they expecting to see? Genius, yes; but the plain, early tailored pieces, like the bumster trousers and perfectly cut jackets, told a lot. The man knew what he was doing. Knowledge was his revolution. And whether or not he could see it, Mr. McQueen had built a durable brand. The Met show -- and the royal wedding dress designed by his successor, Sarah Burton -- was proof of that. 2 If you know anything about Ms. Burton (her skill, her objectivity, her patience), then it wasn't a surprise that Kate Middleton chose McQueen to make her gown as well as the streamlined dress worn by her sister, Pippa. Ms. Burton is a good listener, and she would have been sensitive to the bride and the overwhelming demands of the occasion. The dress distilled English tradition and needle crafts; its flawless fit and styling were communicated to a television audience of tens of millions, no small thing when the medium is cloth. So far, the Duchess of Cambridge has refused to allow herself to be pushed into the high-fashion trap. She wears clothes beautifully, from Reiss and Zara to McQueen, but the lady is no clothes horse. The last thing she wants to be, it seems, is another Jackie, Grace or Diana.
abstract: Roundup of the top ten most memorable fashion moments of 2011. Photos (M)
headline: The Year In Style

snippet: WHEN it comes to areas awash in well-kept old buildings, Ridgewood, in west-central Queens, might not come to mind as quickly as, say, Brooklyn Heights.     But maybe it should. Its two square miles are packed with eye-catching designs; about 10...
lead_paragraph: WHEN it comes to areas awash in well-kept old buildings, Ridgewood, in west-central Queens, might not come to mind as quickly as, say, Brooklyn Heights. But maybe it should. Its two square miles are packed with eye-catching designs; about 10 percent of it -- 350 buildings -- has landmark status, even if it isn't on the radar of most New Yorkers. And with an additional 940 buildings coming up for a vote before the Landmarks Preservation Commission in the next two years, Ridgewood could soon have nearly 1,300 with landmark status -- about the same number as Brooklyn Heights -- which would mean 40 percent of its cityscape was protected.
headline: Architectural Eye Candy

snippet: POPLACK--Rabbi Alvin Myron, 91, died on December 24, 2011 with his three children by his side. He was predeceased by 66 days by his wife of 66 years, the former Rosalind Schachter. Son of Rabbi Alter and Genia Trakeniski Poplack, he was ordained at...
lead_paragraph: POPLACK--Rabbi Alvin Myron, 91, died on December 24, 2011 with his three children by his side. He was predeceased by 66 days by his wife of 66 years, the former Rosalind Schachter. Son of Rabbi Alter and Genia Trakeniski Poplack, he was ordained at Rabbinical Seminary Chaim Berlin (New York) in 1944. Rabbi Poplack held a Masters from Yeshiva University, and a PhD from Jewish Teachers Seminary. During WWII he served as civilian chaplain in the USO Jewish Welfare Board. He held pulpits in Detroit, MI, Medford, MA, and Lebanon, PA before becoming Rabbi (1956) and Rabbi Emeritus (1986) of the Bellerose Jewish Center (New York). He served as President of the Queens Council for Soviet Jewry, and Secretary of the New York Board of Rabbis. As Senior Chaplain, Rabbi Poplack spearheaded the reconstruction of the International Synagogue at JFK Airport, and was spiritual leader to the JFK community and travelers from all over the world. He was the author of Carved In Granite: Holocaust Memorials in Metropolitan New York Jewish Cemeteries (2003), a work read and endorsed by leading Holocaust scholars. He is profoundly missed by his loving children, grandchildren, great-grandchildren, and by family, friends, colleagues, former congregants and the countless people whose lives he touched.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  POPLACK, RABBI ALVIN MYRON

snippet: 2:10 a.m. | Updated  More than 500 people associated with the Occupy Wall Street movement gathered in Zuccotti Park on Saturday and, in a return to scenes from earlier in the year, the evening began with the sound of drumming and calls of the now...
lead_paragraph: 2:10 a.m. | Updated More than 500 people associated with the Occupy Wall Street movement gathered in Zuccotti Park on Saturday and, in a return to scenes from earlier in the year, the evening began with the sound of drumming and calls of the now familiar slogan, ''We are the 99 percent'' - and it ended with torn-down barricades and a scuffle with police officers. Just after 10:30 p.m. on New Year's Eve, officers carried a person out of the park, prompting protesters to follow behind them, shouting ''Shame!'' The reason the person was escorted away was unclear.

lead_paragraph: Visions of sugarplums and flights of fancy with Frosty won't end with the New Year's hangover if Montreal can help it. The city is home to a new Snow Village (snowvillagecanada.com), a mini-city of snow and ice that includes models of some local landmarks like the Olympic Village. Scheduled to run Jan. 6 to March 31 in Parc Jean-Drapeau, the 1.5-acre village features a 60-seat restaurant with tables made of ice, a convention center with capacity for 200, an Ice Chapel designed for weddings, above, and a 30-room hotel with beds that are simply mattresses placed atop ice pedestals.

snippet: BERKELEY--Norborne, Jr.,Bunny of East Hampton and Manhattan New York and former President of Chemical Bank, died peacefully, at age 89, in his home in East Hampton, on December 29th, 2011 following a two-month illness with congestive heart failure....
lead_paragraph: BERKELEY--Norborne, Jr.,Bunny of East Hampton and Manhattan New York and former President of Chemical Bank, died peacefully, at age 89, in his home in East Hampton, on December 29th, 2011 following a two-month illness with congestive heart failure. Norborne was born June 5, 1922 in Bethlehem, PA, the only son of Norborne Berkeley and Dorothea Randolph Berkeley. His one sister, Dorothea Berkeley Brush, died in 1991. Mr. Berkeley was President of Chemical Bank and Chemical NY Corporation (now JPMorgan Chase) from 1973-1982. He was a Director of both the Corporation and the Bank since 1972, and had been with Chemical since 1950, serving in a variety of positions before becoming President. From January, 1982 until June, 1982 he served as Chairman of the Executive Committee, at which time he retired at the age of 60. Mr. Berkeley was a graduate of the Episcopal High School in Alexandria, Virginia (1941), Yale University, BA, (Class of 1945), where he was a member of the Senior Society, Scroll and Key. He held an LL.B. degree from the University of Virginia (1949) and completed the Advanced Management Program at the Harvard Graduate School of Business Administration in 1966. In World War II, Mr. Berkeley served in Europe with the US Field Artillery, First Army V Corps, from 1943-1945 and participated in five major campaigns, including the Normandy Invasion. During his career, he served on numerous corporate, educational and charitable boards including Freeport McMoran Inc., Uniroyal Inc., Anglo Energy LTD; Tuskegee University, Episcopal High School, New Canaan Country Day School (Board President), Metropolitan Opera (Managing Director), Whitney Museum of American Art, Local Initiatives Support Corporation, LISC, (Chairman), and the Vera Institute of Justice. Mr. Berkeley was appointed by President Ford, and served two Administrations (both Republican and Democratic) on the US Advisory Committee for Trade Negotiations. Mr. Berkeley was an avid and accomplished sportsman throughout his life, including baseball at Yale, squash, skiing and golf. He enjoyed playing his father's ukelele and singing old, family songs; the cultural opportunities in New York City, especially the theatre; and travel around the world. His friendships formed at Yale were very special to him throughout his life and his sense of humor, value system and compassion for his fellow man will always be remembered by his many, many friends and family. He was the very loving and adored husband of Jennifer Puchta Berkeley for twenty one years and had three children by a first marriage to Diane Gould Berkeley: Sally Berkeley Tiller, Raleigh, North Carolina; Dr. Anne Randolph Berkeley, Wilmington, North Carolina; Norborne Berkeley III, Bill New York, NY, plus three wonderful grandchildren: Gabe and Jocelyn Tiller and Carmen Berkeley. Caring nieces, nephews and cousins and, his beloved Labrador retriever, Skye, also survive him. The family kindly requests no flowers and instead, if desired, suggests donations to one's own favorite charity, in Norborne Berkeley Jr.'s memory. A celebration of his life will be held at St. Luke's Episcopal Church, 18 James Lane, East Hampton, NY at 11:00am, on Saturday, January 21st, 2012.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  BERKELEY, NORBORNE, JR.

snippet: Dad started taking me to Gregory's Bar and Restaurant in Kew Gardens, Queens, in 1986, when I was 6. He was single and looking for love. So he bought a black Chrysler Laser hatchback, a white Members Only jacket and sneakers with saw-blade soles. And...
lead_paragraph: Dad started taking me to Gregory's Bar and Restaurant in Kew Gardens, Queens, in 1986, when I was 6. He was single and looking for love. So he bought a black Chrysler Laser hatchback, a white Members Only jacket and sneakers with saw-blade soles. And every other weekend, when I wasn't with my mom, he took me to Gregory's. There are many reasons Gregory's was a magical place. Inside the front door there were two real whale bones, seven feet tall and touching at the top. There was an enormous captain's wheel and the ''crow's nest table'' -- an ordinary table perched about five feet in the air on a large ''mast,'' accessible only by ladder.
abstract: Townies column by writer and former bartender Tara Clancy fondly recalls how her father used to bring her to the local bar; asserts that bars in New York City have all become to homogenized. Drawing (M)
headline: My Dad and I Walked Into a Bar ...

lead_paragraph: Texans will close out 2011 with more questions than answers: How will Gov. Rick Perry's presidential bid play out? How will lawmakers' multibillion-dollar budget cuts affect education, Medicaid and health care? Will the courts ever decide on new State House, Senate and Congressional districts so Texas can hold elections? Here's hoping the next year brings some resolution. Texas Tribune reporters take a look at what to expect in 2012 -- from the continuing Texas drought and debates over transparency in higher education to allegations of prosecutorial misconduct and a high-profile presidential election across Texas' southern border.

snippet: WAINER--Andres Rojas, 1942-2011. Former Agence France Presse and UPI Latin American Desk Correspondent; and later Chilean Press Attache to the US under President Salvador Allende died in his home on December 24, 2011 from complications of primary...
lead_paragraph: WAINER--Andres Rojas, 1942-2011. Former Agence France Presse and UPI Latin American Desk Correspondent; and later Chilean Press Attache to the US under President Salvador Allende died in his home on December 24, 2011 from complications of primary systemic amyloidosis. In the latter half of his life Mr. Rojas was in private practice as a landscape designer. He lived in Petaluma, CA with his wife Catherine, daughter of renowned ophthalmologist Dr. Charles Schepens, and founder of Sausalito Springs, an early certified organic farm in California. He is survived by: his wife Catherine; his daughter Dr. Alicia Rojas, a physician and assistant professor at Columbia University Department of Psychiatry; and his son Clarence, artisan blacksmith and chief engineer for Pacific Coral Reed Foundation's new vessel's maiden voyage to Indonesia. There will be a private Memorial Service on January 7, 2012. Please call (415) 206-0230 for details.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  WAINER, ANDRES ROJAS

lead_paragraph: A Maryland judge is being asked to find CarMax, the automotive retailer, in contempt of court for failing to abide by a 2008 class-action settlement. ''CarMax still does not disclose its vehicles' prior use as short-term rental vehicles,'' according to a filing made last month in the Baltimore County Circuit Court by lawyers for the plaintiffs in the class-action suit.

lead_paragraph: Budget constraints brought on by the bad economy have already made it more difficult for Albany to bail out failing hospitals in the city. North General in Harlem, propped up for years by the local political establishment, closed in 2010. So did St. Vincent's Hospital in Manhattan, and two hospitals in Queens closed in 2009. Brooklyn is next. In the coming year, the state will have to decide how to deal with a few struggling hospitals serving poor communities there. Mergers and reorganizations are on the table, and thousands of jobs and the welfare of tens of thousands of patients are at stake.

snippet: Nothing instructs in the art of efficient travel like following a campaigning presidential candidate.
lead_paragraph: TRAVEL is one of the great perks of being a journalist -- over the years, my job has taken me to places like Los Angeles, Paris and Saudi Arabia. But when I began covering Mitt Romney's presidential bid five months ago as a member of The New York Times political team, I suddenly found myself shuffling through airport security several times a week. I knew a campaign assignment would mean spending hours in overlighted terminals, waiting for flights. What I did not know was how much time and energy I would spend figuring out the logistics of travel -- everything from how to get from Iowa to New Hampshire as quickly as possible the morning after the caucuses, to how to snag a hotel reservation on Mackinac Island, Mich., during a Republican conference when nearly every room had been taken by political operatives.
abstract: Ashley Parker Practical Traveler column shares advice from political campaign reporters on how to travel efficiently. Drawing (M)
headline: Get Them to the Debate on Time: Reporters' Tips

snippet: As long as Bimbo’s 365 Club has been around, its special attraction has been Dolphina, the “girl in a fishbowl.” And Dolphina, the illusion of a tiny mermaid in an underwater grotto, swims on today.
lead_paragraph: In a large fishbowl behind the bar at Bimbo's 365 Club, it looks as if a small naked woman is swimming with the goldfish. This ''girl in the fishbowl'' has been part of the nightclub since it opened in 1931 at 365 Market Street. In 1951, Bimbo's relocated to North Beach. snippet: MINKIN--George. July 18, 1920, died December 25, 2011 at age 91. He was the beloved husband of Helen Minkin. He was the son of Belle Celia Rusitzky and Jacob Minkin, a nationally known labor attorney. He was sibling to Sybil Jackson (deceased) and...
lead_paragraph: MINKIN--George. July 18, 1920, died December 25, 2011 at age 91. He was the beloved husband of Helen Minkin. He was the son of Belle Celia Rusitzky and Jacob Minkin, a nationally known labor attorney. He was sibling to Sybil Jackson (deceased) and Noah Minkin (surviving) of Arlington, Virginia and uncle to Leonard Jackson (deceased) and Marsha Jackson, Larry Jackson and Nancy Riedel (surviving). Mr. Minkin served in the U.S. Army Air Corps during World War II. He received B.A. (1941), LL.B. (1947), and LL.M. (1948) degrees from Harvard University, and from 1948 to 1950, he was Assistant Dean at Harvard Law School. He is a retired partner of Carter Ledyard & Milburn LLP. Over his long career, George earned the trust and respect of clients and colleagues alike. A private memorial service is planned.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  MINKIN, GEORGE

snippet: POLPETTINA, a tiny storefront pizzeria with youthful enthusiasm and Brooklynesque charm, has won serious devotees since it opened in the Crestwood section of Eastchester last March. It's a pizzeria at heart, but what turns heads are the sparkling...
lead_paragraph: POLPETTINA, a tiny storefront pizzeria with youthful enthusiasm and Brooklynesque charm, has won serious devotees since it opened in the Crestwood section of Eastchester last March. It's a pizzeria at heart, but what turns heads are the sparkling salads, the way-above-average pasta dishes, a profoundly good roasted chicken half, and trimly tailored desserts. Polpettina -- ''little meatball'' in Italian, which helps to explain the restaurant's tongue-in-cheek slogan: ''We're not your average pizzeria, and we have the 'balls to prove it'' -- is owned by Kyle Inserra and Michael Abruzese. Although they project an image of regular guys, underscored by the neo-rustic décor, whoever is calling the shots in the kitchen has significant talent.
headline: A Pizzeria With Dishes That Go Beyond the Pie

snippet: The biggest environmental decision for New York State in 2012 will be how to regulate drilling for natural gas on the Marcellus Shale, the rich gas field that stretches from New York to Virginia, using the extraction method known as hydrofracking.   ...
lead_paragraph: The biggest environmental decision for New York State in 2012 will be how to regulate drilling for natural gas on the Marcellus Shale, the rich gas field that stretches from New York to Virginia, using the extraction method known as hydrofracking. Even though drilling will be banned in watersheds supplying New York City's drinking water, public opposition to hydrofracking is strong both in the city and in the areas upstate where the new industry promises economic rewards while posing risks to the environment and water supplies. The Cuomo administration is accepting public comments on its environmental impact document and proposed drilling regulations until Jan. 11. Then the Department of Environmental Conservation will prepare to release its final rules and start issuing drilling permits.
abstract: Mireya Navarro predicts developments in environmental issues in New York State in 2012. Drawing (M)
headline: Environment

snippet: Paperback books of particular interest.
lead_paragraph: THE MASTER SWITCH: The Rise and Fall of Information Empires, by Tim Wu (Vintage, $15.95.) This history of modern communications -- covering phones, radio, television, movies and, finally, the Internet -- is organized around what Wu calls ''the Cycle'': ''from somebody's hobby to somebody's industry; from jury-rigged contraption to slick production marvel; from a freely accessible channel to one strictly controlled by a single corporation or cartel -- from open to closed system.'' WHEN THE THRILL IS GONE, by Walter Mosley (New American Library, $15.) In Mosley's third Leonid McGill mystery, the New York P.I. with a murky history as a mob fixer has a lot to deal with: his best friend lies dying in McGill's apartment; McGill's wife has a new lover; and he's taken the case of a nervous woman who suspects her billionaire husband of plotting her murder.
headline: Paperback Row

snippet: 'BLOOD KNOT,'' the 1961 play that vaulted Athol Fugard into international prominence, features two young South African men, one black and one white, grappling over what the world owes them. ''The Train Driver,'' which Mr. Fugard, above, wrote in...
lead_paragraph: 'BLOOD KNOT,'' the 1961 play that vaulted Athol Fugard into international prominence, features two young South African men, one black and one white, grappling over what the world owes them. ''The Train Driver,'' which Mr. Fugard, above, wrote in 2010, features two older South African men, one black and one white, grappling over what they owe the world. These works bookend a rich career for Mr. Fugard, who turns 80 this June and is being honored this season with four major New York productions. These two plays, along with the 1989 political drama ''My Children! My Africa!,'' make up a big part of the Signature Theater Company's inaugural season in its new home. But first comes ''The Road to Mecca,'' which opens Jan. 17 at the Roundabout Theater Company's American Airlines Theater. Rosemary Harris stars in the 1984 drama as Miss Helen, an Afrikaner widow who earns the mistrust of her village when she begins filling her yard with ambitious, whimsical sculptures after the death of her husband.
abstract: South African playwright Athol Fugard reflects on Signature Theater Company's inaugural season in its new home. Photos (M)2
headline: South Africa's Conscience Reflects

snippet: SOREK--Moshe, M.D.,passed away December 19, 2011. Born November 2, 1936 to Hannah and Aharon Souraski in Haifa, Israel. A graduate of the Hebrew University Medical School in Jerusalem, Moshe emigrated to the United States and started his medical...
lead_paragraph: SOREK--Moshe, M.D.,passed away December 19, 2011. Born November 2, 1936 to Hannah and Aharon Souraski in Haifa, Israel. A graduate of the Hebrew University Medical School in Jerusalem, Moshe emigrated to the United States and started his medical career at the Mount Sinai Medical Center in New York City. Thereafter, for twenty five years, he headed the department of Nuclear Medicine at Brookdale Hospital in Brooklyn, NY. Dr. Sorek was a talented physician and an inspiring teacher. He will be loved and missed by his wife Dalia, son Joe, daughters Michelle and Ruth, grandchildren Molly and Nate, brother Natan and his family, and relatives in Israel. Interment was in Scottsdale, Arizona.

snippet: Readers respond to a recent review of Carl T. Bogus’s “Buckley: William F. Buckley Jr. and the Rise of American Conservatism.”
lead_paragraph: To the Editor: Geoffrey Kabaservice says Carl T. Bogus's biography ''Buckley: William F. Buckley Jr. and the Rise of American Conservatism'' fails to grasp ''the history of the conservative movement whole'' (''Right Man, Right Time,'' Dec. 11). But Kabaservice himself fails to grasp -- or at least does not mention -- what it is that ties Edmund Burke (the originator of modern conservatism), Russell Kirk (one of Burke's ''latter-day adherents'') and Buckley: their staunch support of class differences and domination by elites.
headline: Buckley'

snippet: SOREK--Moshe, M.D.,passed away December 19, 2011. Born November 2, 1936 to Hannah and Aharon Souraski in Haifa, Israel. A graduate of the Hebrew University Medical School in Jerusalem, Moshe emigrated to the United States and started his medical...
lead_paragraph: SOREK--Moshe, M.D.,passed away December 19, 2011. Born November 2, 1936 to Hannah and Aharon Souraski in Haifa, Israel. A graduate of the Hebrew University Medical School in Jerusalem, Moshe emigrated to the United States and started his medical career at the Mount Sinai Medical Center in New York City. Thereafter, for twenty five years, he headed the department of Nuclear Medicine at Brookdale Hospital in Brooklyn, NY. Dr. Sorek was a talented physician and an inspiring teacher. He will be loved and missed by his wife Dalia, son Joe, daughters Michelle and Ruth, grandchildren Molly and Nate, brother Natan and his family, and relatives in Israel. Interment was in Scottsdale, Arizona.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  SOREK, MOSHE, M.D.

lead_paragraph: On July 9, when Derek Jeter hit a home run into the left-field seats at Yankee Stadium, his father, Charles, stood and cheered with the rest of the crowd, his eyes growing moist as the ovation lingered. But Charles Jeter might not have been the proudest father in the stadium that day. For later that afternoon, when the game was over and the fans were gone and the workers were using leaf blowers to chase away runaway hot dog wrappers in the grandstand, Raul Lopez found his eyes tearing up, too.

snippet: Tom Clancy, whose new novel hits the hardcover fiction list at No. 2 this week, is often described as prescient. But is he really?
lead_paragraph: THE USUAL SUSPECTS: Tom Clancy's fans like to describe his macho geek-boy thrillers as prescient, citing among other things his 1994 novel ''Debt of Honor,'' in which a deranged pilot crashes a 747 into the Capitol. On Sept. 11, 2001, Clancy himself played up the overlap on CNN, without mentioning that the book is a ludicrous alarmist fantasy about a corporate-controlled Japan making war on America. In other words, it was less prescient than derivative: ''Rising Sun,'' Michael Crichton's version of ''The Japanese are coming!'' had been a best seller two years before. In a telephone interview on ''Charlie Rose'' later on 9/11, Clancy again seemed out of the loop. As Rose's panelists talked about Osama bin Laden and the possibility of military retaliation, Clancy jumped in petulantly. ''Saying 'Osama bin Laden,' '' he insisted, ''is like Claude Rains in 'Casablanca' saying, 'Round up the usual suspects.' He's simply the usual suspect. But there has been no definitive information linking him to this event. Until there is, talking about him is just a waste of air.'' Later on the program, as the former National Security Adviser Samuel Berger tried to answer a question, Clancy's disembodied voice floated over the set. ''Why is there a car in our driveway?'' he asked, apparently forgetting he was wired for sound. ''Tom, wait till I come to you,'' Rose said.
headline: Inside The List
