snippet: Nothing in 2012 is likely to have a bigger impact on the lives of immigrants in New York than the Obama administration's plan to review every pending case in the nation's immigration courts. The goal is to speed the deportations of convicted...
lead_paragraph: Nothing in 2012 is likely to have a bigger impact on the lives of immigrants in New York than the Obama administration's plan to review every pending case in the nation's immigration courts. The goal is to speed the deportations of convicted criminals while sparing many illegal immigrants who have no criminal records and have deep roots in the community. In the absence of comprehensive revisions to federal immigration law, meanwhile, state governments will continue to move unilaterally on immigration issues. New York remains one of the nation's friendlier states to immigrants, and some legislators are seeking to expand educational opportunities for illegal immigrants by making them eligible for state financial aid and scholarships. The idea has received the backing of the Board of Regents, and a related bill may come up for a vote in 2012.
abstract: KIrk Semple predicts developments in immigration in New York State in 2012. (M)
headline: Immigration

snippet: BE honest: would you rather look at Toby the Lab or the funeral of Kim Jong-il? I thought so.     This is my last post for 2011, an eventful year in fashion, a most peculiar year that saw a feverish spread of luxury brands in places like China and...
lead_paragraph: BE honest: would you rather look at Toby the Lab or the funeral of Kim Jong-il? I thought so. This is my last post for 2011, an eventful year in fashion, a most peculiar year that saw a feverish spread of luxury brands in places like China and Brazil, chasing new wealth, even as insiders saw the Galliano scandal as a sobering episode for an industry that tends to push its talent hard. I wonder, though, if the insider's influence hasn't waned. To be sure, people admire the genuinely talented, and we're attracted to star personalities both on the runway and in the front row. It's also true that fashion, like everything else, runs in cycles - one moment it's guilty of gluttony, the next it regrets the whole thing. But outsiders seldom feel these mood swings; they just know what they want, and the business side of fashion houses (along with the more astute creative directors, like Christopher Bailey of Burberry) has seen to it that they get what they want.
abstract: Cathy Horyn On the Runway column describes the hectic shopping scene at Bloomingdale's during the after-Christmas sales. Photo (M)2

snippet: Across the city's 1,700 parks, the coming year will see much new development as well as the reopening of some long-defunct attractions.     The most intriguing might be the $50 million renovation of the McCarren Park pool in Brooklyn, on the...
lead_paragraph: Across the city's 1,700 parks, the coming year will see much new development as well as the reopening of some long-defunct attractions. The most intriguing might be the $50 million renovation of the McCarren Park pool in Brooklyn, on the Greenpoint-Williamsburg border. One of 11 that opened in 1936 under the reign of Robert Moses, the pool was closed in 1984 after deteriorating badly. In its heyday, it must have felt like a vast lake, accommodating a staggering 6,800 people in its 55,440 square feet. (Under today's codes, that expanse would allow 2,200 bathers.)

snippet: Last year featured the much-anticipated return of an Albany tradition: a Cuomo as governor. This year will restore another: pigs in a blanket.      In the bleak Albany winter, the little things count. A new ethics law brokered by Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo...
lead_paragraph: Last year featured the much-anticipated return of an Albany tradition: a Cuomo as governor. This year will restore another: pigs in a blanket. In the bleak Albany winter, the little things count. A new ethics law brokered by Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo last year lifted what amounted to a ban in 2007 on hors d'oeuvres at receptions for public officials. That means lawmakers can once again enjoy events like the Brooklyn Chamber of Commerce's Brooklyn Night, featuring Nathan's hot dogs, Junior's cheesecake and refreshments from Brooklyn Brewery.

snippet: SHEEHAN--Hyacinthe (nee Contessa). A retired NYC Public School English Teacher and Assistant Dean at Ft. Hamilton High School passed away on December 30, 2011 at the age 88. She was the beloved wife of the late Arthur B. Sheehan. Mrs. Sheehan was the...
lead_paragraph: SHEEHAN--Hyacinthe (nee Contessa). A retired NYC Public School English Teacher and Assistant Dean at Ft. Hamilton High School passed away on December 30, 2011 at the age 88. She was the beloved wife of the late Arthur B. Sheehan. Mrs. Sheehan was the loving mother of James Sheehan and his wife Laureen of Pittsburgh, PA; John Sheehan of Brooklyn, NY; and Catherine S. MacDonald and her husband Louis of Winchester, MA. She was the dear sister of Eileen Gorman and her husband Bernard; and the late Joseph Contessa Jr. She was the daughter of the late Joseph and Elizabeth Contessa. She leaves behind her caring sister-in-law Norma Contessa as well as many nieces and nephews. She was the proud grandmother of Emily and Patrick Sheehan; Katie, Ryan and Douglas MacDonald. Visiting Monday 2-7pm at Clavin Funeral Home 7722 4th Avenue, Brooklyn. Mass of Christian Burial Tuesday 11am at Our Lady of Solace R.C. Church.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  SHEEHAN, HYACINTHE (NEE CONTESSA)

snippet: KABUL, Afghanistan -- In a country desperately in need of a hero, Sayyid Abdullah Hashemi would like to apply for the job.     It would be hard to find a more wretched place to go to work on that goal than at the National Directorate of Orphanages in...
lead_paragraph: KABUL, Afghanistan -- In a country desperately in need of a hero, Sayyid Abdullah Hashemi would like to apply for the job. It would be hard to find a more wretched place to go to work on that goal than at the National Directorate of Orphanages in Afghanistan's Ministry of Labor, Social Affairs, Martyrs and the Disabled, where Mr. Hashemi became the director seven months ago. He wasted little time shaking things up at an agency that had become infamous for orphanages where caregivers stole food out of children's mouths and mattresses from under their bodies.
abstract: Sayyid Abdullah Hashemi, director of Afghanistan's orphanages, is attempting to improve their management as he confronts pervasive corruption and political favoritism. Map, Photos (M)
headline: Orphans' Defender Jostles With Afghan Corruption

snippet: When the sports arena that anchors the $4.9 billion Atlantic Yards project finally opens in September, after more than eight years of lawsuits and construction delays, it will undoubtedly transform Downtown Brooklyn. But will the 19,000-seat Barclays...
lead_paragraph: When the sports arena that anchors the $4.9 billion Atlantic Yards project finally opens in September, after more than eight years of lawsuits and construction delays, it will undoubtedly transform Downtown Brooklyn. But will the 19,000-seat Barclays Center, soon to be home to the Nets and host to Jay-Z, the circus and 200 other events a year, help its neighborhood become an epicenter of entertainment and commerce, as most officials predict? Or will it be a vortex of traffic, trash and other civic headaches, as some residents fear? Wedged into the triangle between Flatbush and Atlantic Avenues, on top of a rebuilt transit hub, the arena has already closed streets, bred rats and infuriated neighbors during its construction. And the ribbon-cutting will not be the end. Forest City Ratner intends to break ground this spring on the first of 16 more buildings planned for the area around the stadium: a 32-story residential tower that could make pioneering use of lower-cost modular construction.

snippet: SCHWARZ--Wolfgang, a clinical psychologist for 62 years, passed away on December 27 at the age of 85. Born in Stuttgart Germany on October 30, 1926, he came to America at the age of seven. He leaves behind the love of his life, his wife Susan, and an...
lead_paragraph: SCHWARZ--Wolfgang, a clinical psychologist for 62 years, passed away on December 27 at the age of 85. Born in Stuttgart Germany on October 30, 1926, he came to America at the age of seven. He leaves behind the love of his life, his wife Susan, and an extraordinary family of 18, including his children: Amy, Casey, Darcy and husband Lloyd, Priscilla and husband Amit, Lydia and husband Alun, Emily, Jaime and wife Jessica, and Noah and wife Mary and five grandchildren: Tamsin, Armand, Sabrina, Saskia and Miles as well as close friends and family and grateful patients. In his words, "It's been a great ride." Remembrance may be made to the New York Academy of Science Wolfgang Schwarz Memorial Fund at nyas.org/ gift.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  SCHWARZ, WOLFGANG

snippet: Readers respond to an article on air miles.
lead_paragraph: To the Editor: Re ''Save your Elite Flier Status While You Can'' (Practical Traveler, Dec. 18), I was seven segments short on Continental to get platinum status (you need 90 segments or 75,000 miles), so I did a crazy mileage run last weekend to get to platinum. All in all, the flights cost $350. The flight attendants were looking at me as if I was nuts, because for each pair of cities, I flew back and forth with the same crew. Saturday was Houston to Dallas to Houston to Austin to Houston; and Sunday was from Dallas to Houston to Austin to Houston. Ah, the crazy things we do to retain status. But it really is worth it to board the plane first (for prime overhead space) and for upgrades (I fly probably three weeks out of every month). Lucy Chen
headline: Elite Flier Status

lead_paragraph: A cover article this weekend about the legality of visual artists' appropriating the images of others misstates the action the Supreme Court took in a 1994 case regarding the group 2 Live Crew's sampling of a Roy Orbison song. The court referred the case back to a lower court and, in the process, clarified the legal standard to be applied; the court did not find fair use in that case.

snippet: MILLER--Dorothee C. 1933-2011. Quogue, New York resident Dorothee C. Miller died on Tuesday, December 20 of cirrhosis of the liver at Stony Brook Medical Center after a five-week hospitalization. She was 78. Ms. Miller was the daughter of Sophie and...
lead_paragraph: MILLER--Dorothee C. 1933-2011. Quogue, New York resident Dorothee C. Miller died on Tuesday, December 20 of cirrhosis of the liver at Stony Brook Medical Center after a five-week hospitalization. She was 78. Ms. Miller was the daughter of Sophie and Lester Cornelius. She grew up in Richmond Hill, NY and attended Jamaica High School, thereafter working variously at The Sperry Company and The Singer Company. She also worked part-time as a fashion and television model for The Harry Conover Agency and Pendleton. Later in life, she went back to school, receiving two Associate Degrees from Queens College, New York. She was predeceased in 1998 by her beloved husband of 21 years, Willie, as well as her cherished longtime companion Robert Lovett, Sr. of Hampton Bays, NY in 2008. Dorothee was always cheery and quick with a smile, generous in her hospitality, unwavering in her opinions, independent to the last, and she will be missed greatly by her family and many friends. Ms. Miller is survived by her sister and brother-in-law, Joan and Richard Gibbs of Oak Creek, CO, her son and daughter-in-law, Todd and Lenore Evans of Remsenburg, NY, her son and daughter-in-law, Scott and Cynthia Evans of Chestertown, NY, and her grandchildren Alyssa, Cole, Casey, Kristin, Cody, and Jessie. According to Ms. Miller's wishes, there will be no funeral or memorial services. Her cremains will be scattered across Long Island Sound by her family. The family would appreciate that in lieu of flowers, a gift donation be made to The Betty Ford Legacy Fund in memory of Dorothee Miller, either online, or by calling 800-854-9211 x4105.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  MILLER, DOROTHEE C

snippet: The ''Texas Miracle,'' which Gov. Rick Perry has credited with creating nearly half of the jobs in the national work force since mid-2009, may have dominated headlines in 2011, but heading into 2012 the state's job growth should look far more...
lead_paragraph: The ''Texas Miracle,'' which Gov. Rick Perry has credited with creating nearly half of the jobs in the national work force since mid-2009, may have dominated headlines in 2011, but heading into 2012 the state's job growth should look far more routine. Richard Fisher, president of the Dallas Federal Reserve, said Texas job growth was likely to remain at about 1.5 percent to 2 percent. While the state gained 289,900 private-sector jobs in the last year, Texas' news is not all good. The state's unemployment rate hovered above 8 percent in 2011, while the rest of the nation improved, and the national unemployment rate dropped to 8.6 percent by November. According to the latest statistics from the Texas Workforce Commission, the state lost 63,900 public-sector jobs, largely as a result of lawmakers' budget cuts, and mostly in public education. Texas is only a few months into those cuts.
headline: Job Growth Expected to Be Routine

snippet: The dispute, mostly about pricing, keeps 1.7 million cable homes from seeing Knicks, Rangers, Islanders, Devils and Buffalo Sabres games.
lead_paragraph: The MSG and MSG Plus networks were removed from Time Warner Cable's New York metropolitan-area and Buffalo systems at midnight Eastern on Saturday, cutting off subscribers from Knicks, Rangers, Islanders, Devils and Buffalo Sabres games. In total, the dispute affects 1.7 million cable homes. Replacing the scheduled programming were messages from Time Warner Cable that included: ''We take pride in bringing viewers the best in sports -- and work hard to keep the price of TV reasonable.''
headline: MSG Leaves Time Warner Systems

snippet: KEMPLER--Cecelia (Sue). The partners, counsel, associates and administrative staff of Dewey & LeBoeuf LLP deeply mourn the passing of our retired partner and dear friend, Sue Kempler. Sue co-chaired the Firm's Insurance Practice and chaired its Life...
lead_paragraph: KEMPLER--Cecelia (Sue). The partners, counsel, associates and administrative staff of Dewey & LeBoeuf LLP deeply mourn the passing of our retired partner and dear friend, Sue Kempler. Sue co-chaired the Firm's Insurance Practice and chaired its Life Insurance Practice. She was the first woman on the Firm's Executive Committee and the Managing Partner of the Washington DC office. After her retirement, she served on the Board of AEGON U.S. and on the Supervisory Board of AEGON N.V., and she was the founding Director of the Kaye School of Finance, Insurance and Economics at Florida Atlantic University. Law was Sue's second career, and she pursued it with passion and boundless energy. She was an inspirational leader, mentor, role model, partner and friend. She was a shrewd and highly skilled lawyer who was always the absolute personification of client service. She was wise, warm and witty, charming, generous and fun. And always elegant. She fought her final battle with the great courage, dignity and determination that characterized her life. We extend our condolences to Sue's beloved partner of 31 years and spouse, Virginia Ellen Cropper, and to her family. Donations in Sue's memory can be made to: Boca Raton Regional Hospital Foundation (Lynn Cancer Institute) re: Cecelia Sue Kempler, c/o BRRH Foundation, Inc., 745 Meadows Road, Boca Raton, Florida 33486.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  KEMPLER, CECELIA (SUE)

lead_paragraph: Bonnie Marie Foley, a daughter of Dr. Lisa A. Dado and Dr. Michael R. Foley of Paradise Valley, Ariz., and Jay Reid Mangold Jr., the son of Carol W. Mangold and Mr. Mangold Sr. of Fox Chapel, Pa., were married Saturday at the Montelucia Resort in Scottsdale, Ariz. The Rev. C. Raymond Rau, an affiliate of the White Robed Monks of St. Benedict, performed the ceremony with the assistance of L. Sandy Maisel, a friend of the couple and a professor of government at Colby College. The bride, 23, and the bridegroom, 24, are in their second year of law school at William and Mary in Williamsburg, Va. They graduated from Colby, she magna cum laude, he cum laude.

snippet: Adam Henrique, a 21-year-old center playing on a line with Zach Parise and Ilya Kovalchuk, is off to a strong start with 10 goals and 18 assists.
lead_paragraph: NEWARK -- Adam Henrique, a 21-year-old center playing in only his 35th N.H.L. game, hopped over the boards with two other Devils forwards 45 seconds into Saturday's game, and the three quickly pushed the puck into the Pittsburgh Penguins' zone. This is not exactly an unusual development. Henrique's line has been together for nearly two months, and it has generated a host of scoring chances. After the line helped the Devils beat the Penguins, 3-1, Peter DeBoer, the team's first-year coach, did not sound as if he planned to tinker with it anytime soon.
headline: Devils Rookie Henrique Settling In Between Two Stars

snippet: KEMPLER--Cecelia (Sue). The partners, counsel, associates and administrative staff of Dewey & LeBoeuf LLP deeply mourn the passing of our retired partner and dear friend, Sue Kempler. Sue co-chaired the Firm's Insurance Practice and chaired its Life...
lead_paragraph: KEMPLER--Cecelia (Sue). The partners, counsel, associates and administrative staff of Dewey & LeBoeuf LLP deeply mourn the passing of our retired partner and dear friend, Sue Kempler. Sue co-chaired the Firm's Insurance Practice and chaired its Life Insurance Practice. She was the first woman on the Firm's Executive Committee and the Managing Partner of the Washington DC office. After her retirement, she served on the Board of AEGON U.S. and on the Supervisory Board of AEGON N.V., and she was the founding Director of the Kaye School of Finance, Insurance and Economics at Florida Atlantic University. Law was Sue's second career, and she pursued it with passion and boundless energy. She was an inspirational leader, mentor, role model, partner and friend. She was a shrewd and highly skilled lawyer who was always the absolute personification of client service. She was wise, warm and witty, charming, generous and fun. And always elegant. She fought her final battle with the great courage, dignity and determination that characterized her life. We extend our condolences to Sue's beloved partner of 31 years and spouse, Virginia Ellen Cropper, and to her family. Donations in Sue's memory can be made to: Boca Raton Regional Hospital Foundation (Lynn Cancer Institute) re: Cecelia Sue Kempler, c/o BRRH Foundation, Inc., 745 Meadows Road, Boca Raton, Florida 33486.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  KEMPLER, CECELIA (SUE)

snippet: After more than a decade in which San Francisco politics was partly defined by antidevelopment and historic preservation forces, a backlash has begun.
lead_paragraph: Susan Beckstead stepped out of her sky-blue, three-story classical revival Victorian on Pierce Street -- the one with bay windows, dentil and egg-and-dart molding, a modillion cornice and balustrade-lined flat roof -- to show a visitor around her 120-year-old neighborhood bordering Duboce Park in central San Francisco. Across the street her neighbor was finishing a $1 million remodeling of his 1898 taupe-colored, three-and-a-half-story Queen Anne Victorian, a process that so far has taken a year because of delays in getting permits. At the opposite end of Ms. Beckstead's block, workers toiled on the roof of a pink, 1905 Queen Anne triplex, where restoration is still under way a year after the initial permit application, owing in part to a dispute with neighbors over the appropriateness of a proposed street-facing dormer window.
headline: An Unlikely Group Rebels Against Preservation Districts

snippet: FLEISIG--Ross, an aerospace engineer for over 55 years, died in Binghamton, NY at age 90. Born in Montreal, Canada, Mr. Fleisig grew up in Forest Hills, Queens and lived most of his life in Garden City, New York. He received Bachelor's and Master's...
lead_paragraph: FLEISIG--Ross, an aerospace engineer for over 55 years, died in Binghamton, NY at age 90. Born in Montreal, Canada, Mr. Fleisig grew up in Forest Hills, Queens and lived most of his life in Garden City, New York. He received Bachelor's and Master's Degrees in Engineering from Polytechnic University. Mr. Fleisig enjoyed a long career as an aerospace engineer, working for Chance Vought Aircraft, Sperry Gyroscope Corporation, and the Grumman Corporation. As Spacecraft Team Manager at Grumman during the development of the Apollo Lunar Module, he directed a team integral to the success of the Apollo 11 LM-5 Eagle, the first spacecraft to land humans on the moon. Mr. Fleisig was a member of many professional organizations, including the American Astronautical Society, National Society of Professional Engineers, and American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics. He was an accomplished author and lecturer, receiving numerous honors from private and governmental organizations, and was also a member of the Mineola-Garden City Rotary Club, Garden City Casino, and the Garden City Ski Club. Mr. Fleisig was married to Marjorie Marie Hall, who predeceased him in 2000. He is survived by their two daughters Ann Machlin and Dale Gallis, and two grandchildren Russell Gallis and Thea Gallis Musselman.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  FLEISIG, ROSS

snippet: A reader responds to a recent essay about rereading books.
lead_paragraph: To the Editor: David Bowman's essay ''Read It Again, Sam'' (Dec. 4) called to mind an anecdote dear to Jane Austen devotees. The Oxford philosopher Gilbert Ryle, when asked if he ever read novels, replied: ''Oh yes. All six. Every year.'' It's worth remembering, though, that just as no two siblings ever have the same parents, no one ever reads the same book twice.
headline: Read It Again, Sam'

snippet: <!-- HELEN  FRANKENTHALER -->FRANKENTHALER--Helen. The Board of Trustees and the Staff of the Whitney Museum of American Art mourn the loss of Helen Frankenthaler. Her searing intellect and fearless innovations launched a new direction for postwar...
lead_paragraph: FRANKENTHALER--Helen. The Board of Trustees and the Staff of the Whitney Museum of American Art mourn the loss of Helen Frankenthaler. Her searing intellect and fearless innovations launched a new direction for postwar painting. By experimenting with the qualities of paint and canvas, she was able to create, in her own words, "explosive landscapes, worlds and distances, held on a flat surface." Frankenthaler's work was first shown at the Whitney in 1955 and has subsequently been included in over 40 exhibitions at the Museum. A mid-career retrospective of her work was organized by the Whitney in 1969. The Museum is also proud to hold close to a dozen works in our permanent collection; the first of which, Blue Territory, was acquired from the 1955 Annual. We extend our deepest sympathy to her husband, Stephen M. DuBrul Jr., and her stepdaughters, Jeannie and Lise Motherwell. Flora Miller Biddle, Honorary Chairman Leonard A. Lauder, Chairman Emeritus Robert J. Hurst, Co-Chairman Brooke Garber Neidich, Co-Chairman Neil G. Bluhm, President Adam D. Weinberg Alice Pratt Brown, Director Donna De Salvo, Chief Curator and Deputy Director for Programs
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  FRANKENTHALER, HELEN

lead_paragraph: BELLOW--Alexandra (Sondra). The officers and staff of The Segal Company mourn the untimely passing of our dear colleague and friend. Sondra was a warm and wonderful person, with many strengths and talents. During her 28-year career with our firm, Sondra helped establish our human resources function, served as its senior officer in charge of employee relations, and provided HR consulting to several of our business units. We send our deepest sympathy to her family. Joseph A. LoCicero, President and CEO Howard Fluhr, Chairman Robert D. Krinsky, Chair Emeritus

lead_paragraph: HANDLER--Evelyn. The family of Evelyn Handler mourns the loss of a loving and devoted wife, mother, sister and grandmother. Through the many accomplishments over an illustrious career that spans Hunter College, the University of New Hampshire, Brandeis University, the California Academy of Sciences and Board of Director positions that include the Student Loan Corporation, Evelyn improved the lives of thousands upon thousands of young people with boundless energy, dedication, creativity and a remarkable understanding of how to make an institution "great." We will miss her love, guidance and support without measure. In lieu of flowers, remembrances may be made to the University of New Hampshire School of Law, 2 White St, Concord, NH 03301.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  HANDLER, EVELYN

snippet: BERKELEY--Norborne, Jr., â€œBunnyâ€ of East Hampton...
lead_paragraph: BERKELEY--Norborne, Jr., â€œBunnyâ€ of East Hampton and Manhattan New York and former President of Chemical Bank, died peacefully, at age 89, in his home in East Hampton, on December 29th, 2011 following a two-month illness with congestive heart failure. Norborne was born June 5, 1922 in Bethlehem, PA, the only son of Norborne Berkeley and Dorothea Randolph Berkeley. His one sister, Dorothea Berkeley Brush, died in 1991. Mr. Berkeley was President of Chemical Bank and Chemical NY Corporation (now JPMorgan Chase) from 1973-1982. He was a Director of both the Corporation and the Bank since 1972, and had been with Chemical since 1950, serving in a variety of positions before becoming President. From January, 1982 until June, 1982 he served as Chairman of the Executive Committee, at which time he retired at the age of 60. Mr. Berkeley was a graduate of the Episcopal High School in Alexandria, Virginia (1941), Yale University, BA, (Class of 1945), where he was a member of the Senior Society, Scroll and Key. He held an LL.B. degree from the University of Virginia (1949) and completed the Advanced Management Program at the Harvard Graduate School of Business Administration in 1966. In World War II, Mr. Berkeley served in Europe with the US Field Artillery, First Army V Corps, from 1943-1945 and participated in five major campaigns, including the Normandy Invasion. During his career, he served on numerous corporate, educational and charitable boards including Freeport McMoran Inc., Uniroyal Inc., Anglo Energy LTD; Tuskegee University, Episcopal High School, New Canaan Country Day School (Board President), Metropolitan Opera (Managing Director), Whitney Museum of American Art, Local Initiatives Support Corporation, â€œLISCâ€, (Chairman), and the Vera Institute of Justice. Mr. Berkeley was appointed by President Ford, and served two Administrations (both Republican and Democratic) on the US Advisory Committee for Trade Negotiations. Mr. Berkeley was an avid and accomplished sportsman throughout his life, including baseball at Yale, squash, skiing and golf. He enjoyed playing his father's ukelele and singing old, family songs; the cultural opportunities in New York City, especially the theatre; and travel around the world. His friendships formed at Yale were very special to him throughout his life and his sense of humor, value system and compassion for his fellow man will always be remembered by his many, many friends and family. He was the very loving and adored husband of Jennifer Puchta Berkeley for twenty one years and had three children by a first marriage to Diane Gould Berkeley: Sally Berkeley Tiller, Raleigh, North Carolina; Dr. Anne Randolph Berkeley, Wilmington, North Carolina; Norborne Berkeley III, â€œBillâ€ New York, NY, plus three wonderful grandchildren: Gabe and Jocelyn Tiller and Carmen Berkeley. Caring nieces, nephews and cousins and, his beloved Labrador retriever, Skye, also survive him. The family kindly requests no flowers and instead, if desired, suggests donations to one's own favorite charity, in Norborne Berkeley Jr.'s memory. A celebration of his life will be held at St. Luke's Episcopal Church, 18 James Lane, East Hampton, NY at 11:00am, on Saturday, January 21st, 2012.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  BERKELEY, NORBORNE

snippet: Spain’s new conservative government forecast the country’s 2011 budget deficit at 8 percent of its gross domestic product.
lead_paragraph: MADRID -- Spain's new conservative government revised upward its forecast for the country's 2011 budget deficit, saying it would represent 8 percent of its gross domestic product, up from the 6 percent target of the last government. The new administration approved 8.9 billion euros ($11.5 billion) in spending cuts Friday and maintained a freeze on civil servants' salaries and a freeze on practically all government hiring, said Soraya Sáenz de Santamaria, a government spokeswoman.
headline: Spain Raises Deficit Forecast

snippet: FRANKENTHALER--Helen. The Board of Trustees and the Staff of the Whitney Museum of American Art mourn the loss of Helen Frankenthaler. Her searing intellect and fearless innovations launched a new direction for postwar painting. By experimenting with...
lead_paragraph: FRANKENTHALER--Helen. The Board of Trustees and the Staff of the Whitney Museum of American Art mourn the loss of Helen Frankenthaler. Her searing intellect and fearless innovations launched a new direction for postwar painting. By experimenting with the qualities of paint and canvas, she was able to create, in her own words, "explosive landscapes, worlds and distances, held on a flat surface." Frankenthaler's work was first shown at the Whitney in 1955 and has subsequently been included in over 40 exhibitions at the Museum. A mid-career retrospective of her work was organized by the Whitney in 1969. The Museum is also proud to hold close to a dozen works in our permanent collection; the first of which, Blue Territory, was acquired from the 1955 Annual. We extend our deepest sympathy to her husband, Stephen M. DuBrul Jr., and her stepdaughters, Jeannie and Lise Motherwell. Flora Miller Biddle, Honorary Chairman Leonard A. Lauder, Chairman Emeritus Robert J. Hurst, Co-Chairman Brooke Garber Neidich, Co-Chairman Neil G. Bluhm, President Adam D. Weinberg Alice Pratt Brown, Director Donna De Salvo, Chief Curator and Deputy Director for Programs
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  FRANKENTHALER, HELEN

snippet: Big-box stores may be worrying about their sales on Black Friday, Mega Monday and all the days in between, but sellers of high-end contemporary art seem to have done well this year. On the evidence of some auction results, at least, the market for...
lead_paragraph: Big-box stores may be worrying about their sales on Black Friday, Mega Monday and all the days in between, but sellers of high-end contemporary art seem to have done well this year. On the evidence of some auction results, at least, the market for such art rose significantly as jittery investors put their money into art instead of stocks, Bloomberg News reported. ''The art market is a place for new people these days,'' Christophe Van de Weghe, a New York dealer, was quoted as saying. ''There are Americans nobody has seen before who are excited by this world and who want an alternative to shares. And then there are buyers coming in from places like India and China.''
abstract: Auction results from 2011 shows reflect how high-end contemporary art market has continued to rebound, as jittery investors put their money into art instead of stocks. (M)1
headline: A Good Year For High-End Art

snippet: A performing arts center planned for the World Trade Center site has taken a step forward with the naming of a board by the National September 11 Memorial & Museum foundation. On the list are the developers Larry Silverstein and John E. Zuccotti;...
lead_paragraph: A performing arts center planned for the World Trade Center site has taken a step forward with the naming of a board by the National September 11 Memorial & Museum foundation. On the list are the developers Larry Silverstein and John E. Zuccotti; Christy Ferer, founder and chief executive of the Vidicom video company; Julie Menin, chairwoman of Community Board 1; and Zenia Mucha, executive vice president of the Walt Disney Company. Joseph C. Daniels, president of the Sept. 11 foundation, added that Patricia E. Harris, the first deputy mayor, would serve as an ex-officio member representing Mayor Michael R. Bloomberg. Naming a board was a prerequisite for tapping into $100 million that the Lower Manhattan Development Corporation had set aside for the center, which is to be designed by Frank Gehry. Even though the deadline was the end of this year, the naming of the board members, like other issues related to the World Trade Center site, including financing for the Sept. 11 museum, had been held up by tension between Mayor Bloomberg and Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo. The governor still has the option of naming someone to the board.
abstract: National September 11 Memorial & Museum foundation names board of performing arts center planned for World Trade Center site, allowing plan to move forward. (M)
headline: Board for Arts Center At Trade Center Site

lead_paragraph: DES MOINES -- Newt Gingrich openly cried on Friday morning during an event with a group of mothers in an Iowa coffee shop as he described his own mother's illness. The Republican pollster Frank Luntz had asked Mr. Gingrich to recall a moment with his mother that changed his life. Mr. Gingrich started to describe the illness at the end of her life, when she struggled with depression and bipolar disease.

snippet: Kurds took to the streets a day after the Turkish authorities admitted that airstrikes in northern Iraq intended to kill Kurdish militants had instead claimed the lives of 35 civilians.
lead_paragraph: ISTANBUL -- Kurdish separatist banners in red, yellow and green draped the coffins of 35 Turkish civilians and fluttered among mourning crowds on Friday, a day after the Turkish authorities admitted that airstrikes in northern Iraq intended to kill Kurdish militants had instead claimed the lives of young smugglers. In Istanbul, home to a large Kurdish community, angry protesters clashed with the police for a second day, hurling stones at security vehicles that used tear gas and pressurized water to disperse crowds. The crowd blamed Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan, chanting ''Murderer Erdogan,'' local agencies reported.
headline: Kurds Protest Airstrike Killing Dozens in Turkey

snippet: Alex Ferguson has warmed up to the last weekend of 2011 with two 5-0 victories, and a third on Saturday could take his team to where it started the year: alone atop the Premier League.
lead_paragraph: Just because a man reaches his 70th birthday on Saturday is no reason to give him everything he wants. But Alex Ferguson, the Manchester United manager for 25 years, has warmed up to the last weekend of 2011 with two 5-0 victories, and a third on Saturday could take his team to where it started the year: alone atop the Premier League. A holiday game Friday was to precede the weekend action, though, with Liverpool facing Newcastle United. Liverpool's second season under its current American ownership has faltered of late. Its Uruguayan striker, Luis Suárez, was to start what could be a nine-game ban, and Andy Carroll, for whom Liverpool paid Newcastle £35 million, or about $54 million, last January, has yet to look anything like the powerful center forward he appeared to be with Newcastle.
headline: United Aims for Sole Possession of Premier League Lead

snippet: An article on Friday about the closing of a discount retailer in Boston misstated the name of the store in the headline and in some references. The store is Filene's Basement, not simply Filene's. (Filene's Basement was opened in 1909 in the basement...
lead_paragraph: An article on Friday about the closing of a discount retailer in Boston misstated the name of the store in the headline and in some references. The store is Filene's Basement, not simply Filene's. (Filene's Basement was opened in 1909 in the basement of Filene's department store in Boston. The two became separate companies in 1991. Federated Department Stores acquired the Filene's department stores in 2005 and closed some and converted the remaining stores to Macy's in 2006.)
headline: Corrections

snippet: Theater     NEW BROADWAY MUSICAL     The crashing, crushing and smashing sounds that regularly emanate from ''Spider-Man: Turn Off the Dark'' -- the accident-prone $65 million musical now (and perhaps forever) in previews -- have all but drowned out...
lead_paragraph: Theater NEW BROADWAY MUSICAL The crashing, crushing and smashing sounds that regularly emanate from ''Spider-Man: Turn Off the Dark'' -- the accident-prone $65 million musical now (and perhaps forever) in previews -- have all but drowned out the advance word on a show that, in a Spidey-free season, would surely have some of the loudest buzz on Broadway. That's ''The Book of Mormon'' (opening March 24 at the Eugene O'Neill Theater), a singing, dancing history of the founding of the Mormon Church that also tells the parallel story of two contemporary disciples who go to spread Joseph Smith's gospel in Uganda.
headline: Looking Ahead; Onstage, the Irreverent (and Maybe Irresistible)

snippet: LeVINE--Robert Caldwell, died December 23, 2011 peacefully at his home in Naples, Florida. Robert is the beloved father of Jeananne Stine of Baltimore, MD, Robert B. LeVine of Brussels, Belgium, Mary LeVine of Naples, FL, Ron LeVine of New York City,...
lead_paragraph: LeVINE--Robert Caldwell, died December 23, 2011 peacefully at his home in Naples, Florida. Robert is the beloved father of Jeananne Stine of Baltimore, MD, Robert B. LeVine of Brussels, Belgium, Mary LeVine of Naples, FL, Ron LeVine of New York City, NY and Jamie LeVine of Mamaroneck, NY and adored grandfather of Eric LeVine, Maryruth Stine, Marc LeVine, Sarabeth Stine, Terry LeVine, Charlie Stine, James Hickey and Ella LeVine. Born February 6, 1933 to Harry and Mary LeVine in Pittsburgh, PA, Robert graduated from Bethany College in 1955 and was married to Jean Bovill in 1956. The couple moved to Manhattan in 1959 and were long-time residents of New York City and Westchester County, NY before Robert retired from JP Morgan Investments; where he served as Managing Director. Jean died in 2008 and Bob joins her now just in time for Christmas. An elegant pair, they were an example of true love and devotion. Our home was filled with laughter and music, and our father was a true gentleman. We couldn't have been luckier. Friends will be received in Naples, FL Thursday December 29, from 3:00pm to 5:00pm, at the Diplomat, 1919 Gulf Shore Boulevard North. Friends will be received in Pittsburgh, PA Friday January 6, 2012 from 2:00pm to 4:00pm and 6: 00pm to 8:00pm at McDonald-Linn Funeral Home, 529 California Ave., Pittsburgh, PA with a Funeral Service the following day at 10:00am. Burial will take place at Union Dale Cemetery. In lieu of flowers, donations in honor of Robert C. LeVine may be sent to Bethany College, Erickson Alumni Center, Bethany W. Va., 26032. For online condolences, please visit www.fullerfuneralhome.com
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  LEVINE, ROBERT CALDWELL

snippet: Around the world, middle classes ordinarily devoted to the pursuit of washing machines and flatter screens decided this year, more forcefully than in recent memory, that the world was their problem.
lead_paragraph: NEW DELHI -- The year that flees us this weekend was violent and hopeful, angry and generative. Was it a good year? It depends where you stood -- among the old or young, in the sclerotic West or vital East, in a surging Arab square or gilded Arab palace. It felt like a year unusually pregnant with consequence. From Tunisia to Egypt to Libya to Japan, from a royal wedding to child murders in the Norwegian woods to a maritime funeral for a terrorist overlord, from a reconfigured Europe to the end of the United States' adventure in Iraq, one had the sense of events skipping from the happening straight to the history books.
headline: The Middles Found Their Voice in 2011

snippet: BERKELEY--Norborne, Jr.,Bunny of East Hampton and Manhattan New York and former President of Chemical Bank, died peacefully, at age 89, in his home in East Hampton, on December 29th, 2011 following a two-month illness with congestive heart failure....
lead_paragraph: BERKELEY--Norborne, Jr.,Bunny of East Hampton and Manhattan New York and former President of Chemical Bank, died peacefully, at age 89, in his home in East Hampton, on December 29th, 2011 following a two-month illness with congestive heart failure. Norborne was born June 5, 1922 in Bethlehem, PA, the only son of Norborne Berkeley and Dorothea Randolph Berkeley. His one sister, Dorothea Berkeley Brush, died in 1991. Mr. Berkeley was President of Chemical Bank and Chemical NY Corporation (now JPMorgan Chase) from 1973-1982. He was a Director of both the Corporation and the Bank since 1972, and had been with Chemical since 1950, serving in a variety of positions before becoming President. From January, 1982 until June, 1982 he served as Chairman of the Executive Committee, at which time he retired at the age of 60. Mr. Berkeley was a graduate of the Episcopal High School in Alexandria, Virginia (1941), Yale University, BA, (Class of 1945), where he was a member of the Senior Society, Scroll and Key. He held an LL.B. degree from the University of Virginia (1949) and completed the Advanced Management Program at the Harvard Graduate School of Business Administration in 1966. In World War II, Mr. Berkeley served in Europe with the US Field Artillery, First Army V Corps, from 1943-1945 and participated in five major campaigns, including the Normandy Invasion. During his career, he served on numerous corporate, educational and charitable boards including Freeport McMoran Inc., Uniroyal Inc., Anglo Energy LTD; Tuskegee University, Episcopal High School, New Canaan Country Day School (Board President), Metropolitan Opera (Managing Director), Whitney Museum of American Art, Local Initiatives Support Corporation, LISC, (Chairman), and the Vera Institute of Justice. Mr. Berkeley was appointed by President Ford, and served two Administrations (both Republican and Democratic) on the US Advisory Committee for Trade Negotiations. Mr. Berkeley was an avid and accomplished sportsman throughout his life, including baseball at Yale, squash, skiing and golf. He enjoyed playing his father's ukelele and singing old, family songs; the cultural opportunities in New York City, especially the theatre; and travel around the world. His friendships formed at Yale were very special to him throughout his life and his sense of humor, value system and compassion for his fellow man will always be remembered by his many, many friends and family. He was the very loving and adored husband of Jennifer Puchta Berkeley for twenty one years and had three children by a first marriage to Diane Gould Berkeley: Sally Berkeley Tiller, Raleigh, North Carolina; Dr. Anne Randolph Berkeley, Wilmington, North Carolina; Norborne Berkeley III, Bill New York, NY, plus three wonderful grandchildren: Gabe and Jocelyn Tiller and Carmen Berkeley. Caring nieces, nephews and cousins and, his beloved Labrador retriever, Skye, also survive him. The family kindly requests no flowers and instead, if desired, suggests donations to one's own favorite charity, in Norborne Berkeley Jr.'s memory. A celebration of his life will be held at St. Luke's Episcopal Church, 18 James Lane, East Hampton, NY at 11:00am, on Saturday, January 21st, 2012.

snippet: On ''Fox News Sunday,'' Mike Huckabee claimed that if the weather is bad in Iowa this Tuesday, Representative Ron Paul will win the state caucuses over Mitt Romney, whose supporters are not as dedicated. Current forecasts predict the weather will be...
lead_paragraph: On ''Fox News Sunday,'' Mike Huckabee claimed that if the weather is bad in Iowa this Tuesday, Representative Ron Paul will win the state caucuses over Mitt Romney, whose supporters are not as dedicated. Current forecasts predict the weather will be relatively balmy, with no chance of rain or snow - which, according to Mr. Huckabee, the former governor of Arkansas, will favor Mr. Romney. A 2007 study in the Journal of Politics shows that weather does influence voter turnout in the general election: Every inch of rain tends to decrease turnout by almost one percentage point, while every inch of snow above a precinct's historical average for the week deters roughly half a percentage point of voters.
headline: How the Weather Turns Out

Just as more ordinary people run marathons, compete in triathlons and cycle longer distances, more amateur athletes are also pushing boundaries. The madness is beginning to go mainstream. Traders said there had been signs that the central bank intervened to push the renminbi up at the end of the year.

Recently in Israel, the former Mossad chief Meir Dagan said that a military strike against Iran will result in massive rockets attacks from Iran, Hezbollah and Hamas, and also in considerable loss of Israeli lives. snippet: The rapper C-Murder has failed to convince a Louisiana appeals court that his conviction on a second-degree murder charge was flawed, The Associated Press reported.  In 2009 a jury found C-Murder, whose real name is Corey Miller, guilty of fatally...
lead_paragraph: The rapper C-Murder has failed to convince a Louisiana appeals court that his conviction on a second-degree murder charge was flawed, The Associated Press reported. In 2009 a jury found C-Murder, whose real name is Corey Miller, guilty of fatally shooting a 16-year-old fan during a fight in 2002 at a nightclub in the New Orleans area. Sentenced to life in prison without parole, Mr. Miller appealed the conviction, saying the trial was unfair. But on Wednesday Louisiana's Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the jury's decision. The three-judge panel rejected Mr. Miller's arguments that prosecutors had systematically kept black people off the jury and that the judge had allowed jurors to hear ''prejudicial and unsubstantiated'' testimony.
abstract: Louisiana appeals court upholds rapper C-Murder's second degree murder charge; rapper was found guilty in 2009 of shooting 16-year-old fan during fight at nightclub in New Orleans area. Photo (S)
headline: Appeals Court Upholds C-Murder's Conviction

snippet: Remember when you were a kid and your parents harped on the importance of ''delayed gratification'' to get ahead in life? (You know: Put that birthday money in the piggy bank and save for something nice, instead of blowing it all now on Milky Way...
lead_paragraph: Remember when you were a kid and your parents harped on the importance of ''delayed gratification'' to get ahead in life? (You know: Put that birthday money in the piggy bank and save for something nice, instead of blowing it all now on Milky Way bars.) Well, it turns out that your propensity to wait (or not) is also reflected in your credit score, according to a study from researchers at Columbia and Stanford published online in Psychological Science, a journal of the Association for Psychological Science. (Here's a link to the press release, though the journal itself is behind a pay wall.)
headline: Credit Scores And Patience

snippet: A repeat of ''The Big Bang Theory'' was enough to give CBS an easy ratings victory (in total viewers and in the 18-to-49-year-old demographic) on Thursday, according to Nielsen data. All of the networks had a full slate of repeats, resulting in lower...
lead_paragraph: A repeat of ''The Big Bang Theory'' was enough to give CBS an easy ratings victory (in total viewers and in the 18-to-49-year-old demographic) on Thursday, according to Nielsen data. All of the networks had a full slate of repeats, resulting in lower viewership totals across the broadcast board, but the audience for CBS's geeky comedy has proved to be very loyal, even for previously aired episodes. It still drew 10.2 million total viewers Thursday night, losing less than a third of its fall live audience average of 14.7 million for new episodes. Although its authenticity has been called into question, Discovery Channel's ''Moonshiners'' has frequently found itself to be among the top-rated cable shows on Wednesday nights. The most recent episode tied for the highest-rated cable program among adults 18-to-49 to go with a total of 2.6 million viewers.
headline: On Night of Repeats, 'Big Bang' Stands Out

snippet: China's rise to economic superpower status is built upon an unresolved land struggle with hundreds of millions of lives in the balance.
lead_paragraph: Two weeks ago peasants in Wukan, a fishing village in the prosperous southern Chinese province of Guangdong, took over their village, throwing out local leaders. Because of long unanswered grievances, they risked their lives, barricading roads into the village and facing down the police. Their central concern was the sale of collectively owned village land to property developers, which has impoverished most residents while enriching their leaders. As the Wukan protests evolved into an international media event, a provincial party official, under pressure from Beijing, stepped in and swiftly negotiated a truce acceptable to the villagers. This week Prime Minister Wen Jiabao asserted that ''China can no longer sacrifice farmers' land rights for the sake of reducing the cost of urbanization and industrialization.''
headline: China's Shaky Economic Foundation

It's a nice, personal touch in a business that has long since lost it. Forty two years ago - when Manny was born into the retail record business - companies like Ansonia could barely keep up with the demand for Latin music, from classic trios, romantic duos and swinging mambo bands. headline: A Brooklyn Music Store Resolves to Adapt

lead_paragraph: Before he departed the stage, before the curtain dropped and the N.B.A. plunged into six months of self-imposed darkness, LeBron James gave his critics a stinging farewell to remember. The Miami Heat had just lost the championship to the Dallas Mavericks. James was a prime culprit, for his abysmal fourth-quarter play throughout the finals. To those who resented the Heat's bravado and bluster, this was karmic payoff. So, James was asked, did it bother him that people were celebrating his failure?
abstract: Howard Beck offers memorable sports moment from 2011; notes ill-considered remarks of Miami Heat star forward LeBron James in response to criticism of his performance after Miami lost NBA championship to Dallas Mavericks. Photo (M)
headline: 2011: James Reminds Fans He Is Richer Than They Are

snippet: The 208-run victory was not just a breakthrough, it was a turning point for Sri Lankan cricket after 18 months of misery.
lead_paragraph: DURBAN, SOUTH AFRICA -- For the first time since Muttiah Muralitharan retired, Sri Lanka has finally won a test. The team did it convincingly, by more than 200 runs, and in a country where it had never won in the long format before. There is life for Sri Lanka after the great man Murali.
headline: Sri Lanka Breathes New Life After Test Victory Over South Africa

snippet: Connecticut's 11-game run to the N.C.A.A. men's basketball championship began with a win over DePaul and ended with a victory against Butler, but it will long be remembered for Kemba Walker's winning shot against Pittsburgh on March 10.     With 18...
lead_paragraph: Connecticut's 11-game run to the N.C.A.A. men's basketball championship began with a win over DePaul and ended with a victory against Butler, but it will long be remembered for Kemba Walker's winning shot against Pittsburgh on March 10. With 18 seconds left in their Big East tournament quarterfinal and the score tied, 74-74, the Huskies went through the motions of drawing up plans for the final shot, but there was never any doubt on either bench that Walker would be the one to take it.
abstract: Andrew Das offers memorable sports moment from 2011, choosing Connecticut guard Kemba Walker's winning shot against Pittsburgh in Big East tournament quarterfinals; UConn went on to win NCAA men's basketball national title. Photo (M)
headline: 2011: A Glorious Run by UConn, Then Another

snippet: MINKIN--George. July 18, 1920, died December 25, 2011 at age 91. He was the beloved husband of Helen Minkin. He was the son of Belle Celia Rusitzky and Jacob Minkin, a nationally known labor attorney. He was sibling to Sybil Jackson (deceased) and...
lead_paragraph: MINKIN--George. July 18, 1920, died December 25, 2011 at age 91. He was the beloved husband of Helen Minkin. He was the son of Belle Celia Rusitzky and Jacob Minkin, a nationally known labor attorney. He was sibling to Sybil Jackson (deceased) and Noah Minkin (surviving) of Arlington, Virginia and uncle to Leonard Jackson (deceased) and Marsha Jackson, Larry Jackson and Nancy Riedel (surviving). Mr. Minkin served in the U.S. Army Air Corps during World War II. He received B.A. (1941), LL.B. (1947), and LL.M. (1948) degrees from Harvard University, and from 1948 to 1950, he was Assistant Dean at Harvard Law School. He is a retired partner of Carter Ledyard & Milburn LLP. Over his long career, George earned the trust and respect of clients and colleagues alike. A private memorial service is planned.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  MINKIN, GEORGE

snippet: Once again, a reality television show has viewers asking whether it's real or unreal. This time, the authorities are answering with a no.     The series in question is ''Moonshiners,'' a new entrant on the Discovery Channel that ostensibly shows...
lead_paragraph: Once again, a reality television show has viewers asking whether it's real or unreal. This time, the authorities are answering with a no. The series in question is ''Moonshiners,'' a new entrant on the Discovery Channel that ostensibly shows people in rural Virginia who make their own alcohol and the state agents who pursue them. In an online interview one person suggested that he actually made moonshine, which is illegal; in response, the agency that regulates alcohol in Virginia said on Thursday that the show was just a dramatization. ''If illegal activity was actually taking place, the Virginia ABC Bureau of Law Enforcement would have taken action,'' the agency told The Associated Press.
abstract: Agency that regulates alcohol in Virginia says that television reality series Moonshiners, which ostensibly depicts people making their own alcohol, is scripted and not real; making moonshine is illegal. Photo (S)
headline: Dang Revenuers: Agency Miffed by 'Moonshiners'

snippet: New Jersey serves as an unlikely muse for creatives around the world.
lead_paragraph: A recent article in our magazine discussed the work of the artist Shea Hembrey, who fabricated an astounding catalog filled with the work of 100 artists of his own creation. The article by Sara Corbett discusses Hembrey's life, his work and, briefly, his locale while completing the catalog: New Jersey. Frenchtown, to be exact. For me, as a native of the state, this small part of the story filled me with pride. The Garden State is so often mocked for everything from its accent to its aroma that my ears perk up whenever it's mentioned without contempt. Perhaps because of this proclivity, I've noticed a handful of artists' projects recently that have been influenced or directly inspired by the state, even if nowhere near it. Here are a few of my favorites:
abstract: New Jersey serves as an unlikely muse for creatives around the world.
headline: The Fertile Ground of the Garden State

snippet: Discovery Channel's "Moonshiners" has frequently found itself to be among the top-rated cable shows on Wednesday nights.
lead_paragraph: A repeat of "The Big Bang Theory" was enough to give CBS an easy ratings victory (in total viewers and in the 18-to-49-year-old demographic) on Thursday, according to Nielsen data. All of the networks had a full slate of repeats, resulting in lower viewership totals across the broadcast board, but the audience for CBS's geeky comedy has proved to be very loyal, even for previously aired episodes. It still drew 10.2 million total viewers Thursday night, losing less than a third of its fall live audience average of 14.7 million for new episodes.
abstract: Discovery Channel's "Moonshiners" has frequently found itself to be among the top-rated cable shows on Wednesday nights.
headline: Modestly Performing Repeats on Networks, 'Moonshiners' Makes Gains on Cable

snippet: <!-- JOHN  CHAMBERLAIN -->CHAMBERLAIN--John. The Board of Trustees and the Staff of the Whitney Museum of American Art note with sadness the death of John Chamberlain. One of the most important American sculptors of our time, Chamberlain's...
lead_paragraph: CHAMBERLAIN--John. The Board of Trustees and the Staff of the Whitney Museum of American Art note with sadness the death of John Chamberlain. One of the most important American sculptors of our time, Chamberlain's distinctive approach and intuitive understanding of material, gesture, and space amounted to a new sculptural language. He was the consummate artist; his curiosity knew no bounds and his influence will be felt for years to come. The Whitney is proud to hold a number of Chamberlain's works in our permanent collection, the first of which was acquired in 1963. Over 30 exhibitions at the Museum have included his work. We extend our condolences to his wife, Prudence Fairweather, and his children, Angus, Duncan, Alexandra and Phoebe. Flora Miller Biddle, Honorary Chairman; Leonard A. Lauder, Chairman Emeritus; Robert J. Hurst, Co-Chairman; Brooke Garber Neidich, Co-Chairman; Neil G. Bluhm, President; Adam D. Weinberg, Alice Pratt Brown Director; Donna De Salvo, Chief Curator and Deputy Director for Programs
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  CHAMBERLAIN, JOHN

snippet: <!-- ROBERT  LEVINE -->LeVINE--Robert Caldwell, died December 23, 2011 peacefully at his home in Naples, Florida. Robert is the beloved father of Jeananne Stine of Baltimore, MD, Robert B. LeVine of Brussels, Belgium, Mary LeVine of Naples, FL, Ron...
lead_paragraph: LeVINE--Robert Caldwell, died December 23, 2011 peacefully at his home in Naples, Florida. Robert is the beloved father of Jeananne Stine of Baltimore, MD, Robert B. LeVine of Brussels, Belgium, Mary LeVine of Naples, FL, Ron LeVine of New York City, NY and Jamie LeVine of Mamaroneck, NY and adored grandfather of Eric LeVine, Maryruth Stine, Marc LeVine, Sarabeth Stine, Terry LeVine, Charlie Stine, James Hickey and Ella LeVine. Born February 6, 1933 to Harry and Mary LeVine in Pittsburgh, PA, Robert graduated from Bethany College in 1955 and was married to Jean Bovill in 1956. The couple moved to Manhattan in 1959 and were long-time residents of New York City and Westchester County, NY before Robert retired from JP Morgan Investments; where he served as Managing Director. Jean died in 2008 and Bob joins her now just in time for Christmas. An elegant pair, they were an example of true love and devotion. Our home was filled with laughter and music, and our father was a true gentleman. We couldn't have been luckier. Friends will be received in Naples, FL Thursday December 29, from 3:00pm to 5:00pm, at the Diplomat, 1919 Gulf Shore Boulevard North. Friends will be received in Pittsburgh, PA Friday January 6, 2012 from 2:00pm to 4:00pm and 6: 00pm to 8:00pm at McDonald-Linn Funeral Home, 529 California Ave., Pittsburgh, PA with a Funeral Service the following day at 10:00am. Burial will take place at Union Dale Cemetery. In lieu of flowers, donations in honor of Robert C. LeVine may be sent to Bethany College, Erickson Alumni Center, Bethany W. Va., 26032. For online condolences, please visit www.fullerfuneralhome.com
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  LEVINE, ROBERT

snippet: <!-- EDWARD J. GARVEY -->GARVEY--Edward J. The AHRC New York City Board of Directors, senior staff and membership mourn the passing of AHRC New York City Board Member, Edward J. Garvey, and extend sympathy to his beloved and bereaved family. Ed was a...
lead_paragraph: GARVEY--Edward J. The AHRC New York City Board of Directors, senior staff and membership mourn the passing of AHRC New York City Board Member, Edward J. Garvey, and extend sympathy to his beloved and bereaved family. Ed was a member of AHRC since 1967 and became a member of the Board of Directors in 1969. During those years he served as Chapter President, as well as in other Board Officer positions, and he was the AHRC Annual Dinner Chairperson in 1981 and 2002 and was presented with AHRC's Anne Kraus Memorial Award for volunteerism in 2004. Ed was a strong, longtime supporter of the importance of direct care staff, and was an influential force of the AHRC Board in advocating on behalf of direct care staff. We offer our sincere condolences to Ed's wife, Rita, and children Edward, Robert, Joseph and Peter, and grandchildren. His son, Peter resides in an AHRC group residence. Ed will be remembered by his "AHRC family" and will be greatly missed. The funeral is scheduled to be held Saturday morning at 9:45am at St. Thomas Apostle Church, 87-49 87th St. in Woodhaven, NY. Dr. Melvin Gertner, President AHRC New York City; Dr. Lorrie Henderson, Executive Director, AHRC New York City
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  GARVEY, EDWARD J.

snippet: <!-- GEORGE  MINKIN -->MINKIN--George. July 18, 1920, died December 25, 2011 at age 91. He was the beloved husband of Helen Minkin. He was the son of Belle Celia Rusitzky and Jacob Minkin, a nationally known labor attorney. He was sibling to Sybil...
lead_paragraph: MINKIN--George. July 18, 1920, died December 25, 2011 at age 91. He was the beloved husband of Helen Minkin. He was the son of Belle Celia Rusitzky and Jacob Minkin, a nationally known labor attorney. He was sibling to Sybil Jackson (deceased) and Noah Minkin (surviving) of Arlington, Virginia and uncle to Leonard Jackson (deceased) and Marsha Jackson, Larry Jackson and Nancy Riedel (surviving). Mr. Minkin served in the U.S. Army Air Corps during World War II. He received B.A. (1941), LL.B. (1947), and LL.M. (1948) degrees from Harvard University, and from 1948 to 1950, he was Assistant Dean at Harvard Law School. He is a retired partner of Carter Ledyard & Milburn LLP. Over his long career, George earned the trust and respect of clients and colleagues alike. A private memorial service is planned.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  MINKIN, GEORGE

snippet: <!-- CECELIA  KEMPLER -->KEMPLER--Cecelia (Sue). The partners, counsel, associates and administrative staff of Dewey & LeBoeuf LLP deeply mourn the passing of our retired partner and dear friend, Sue Kempler. Sue co-chaired the Firm's Insurance...
lead_paragraph: KEMPLER--Cecelia (Sue). The partners, counsel, associates and administrative staff of Dewey & LeBoeuf LLP deeply mourn the passing of our retired partner and dear friend, Sue Kempler. Sue co-chaired the Firm's Insurance Practice and chaired its Life Insurance Practice. She was the first woman on the Firm's Executive Committee and the Managing Partner of the Washington DC office. After her retirement, she served on the Board of AEGON U.S. and on the Supervisory Board of AEGON N.V., and she was the founding Director of the Kaye School of Finance, Insurance and Economics at Florida Atlantic University. Law was Sue's second career, and she pursued it with passion and boundless energy. She was an inspirational leader, mentor, role model, partner and friend. She was a shrewd and highly skilled lawyer who was always the absolute personification of client service. She was wise, warm and witty, charming, generous and fun. And always elegant. She fought her final battle with the great courage, dignity and determination that characterized her life. We extend our condolences to Sue's beloved partner of 31 years and spouse, Virginia Ellen Cropper, and to her family.â€ Donations in Sue's memory can be made to: Boca Raton Regional Hospital Foundation (Lynn Cancer Institute) re: Cecelia â€œSueâ€ Kempler, c/o BRRH Foundation, Inc., 745 Meadows Road, Boca Raton, Florida 33486.
headline: Paid Notice: Deaths  KEMPLER, CECELIA

snippet: Bordeaux is more distinctive for wines than food, though its vinously sauced dishes are famous, as is its lamb from Pauillac. Indeed, while tasting, it struck me that succulent lamb, with slightly gamy fat, would best unpin the tight embrace of the...
lead_paragraph: Bordeaux is more distinctive for wines than food, though its vinously sauced dishes are famous, as is its lamb from Pauillac. Indeed, while tasting, it struck me that succulent lamb, with slightly gamy fat, would best unpin the tight embrace of the 2008 vintage from the Médoc. I braised chunks of lamb shoulder in wine, gave the dish an edge with lemon zest and white turnips, and added buttery white beans, a classic partner for lamb. If you like canned beans, rinse and drain them, and add in place of the cooked beans, with the turnips, during final simmering.
headline: Wines of The Times: Ready or Not, 2008 Médocs
